# Phase 1: Messaging Abstractions and Data Model

## Dependencies
- _none — start phase_

## Stage 1.1: Core Data Models

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create solution file `AgentSwarm.Messaging.sln` and project `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` targeting .NET 8.
- [ ] Define `MessengerMessage` record with fields: `MessageId`, `ConversationId`, `AgentId`, `TaskId`, `CorrelationId`, `Body`, `Timestamp`, `Severity`.
- [ ] Define `AgentQuestion` record with fields: `QuestionId` (string), `AgentId` (string), `TaskId` (string), `TenantId` (string — the Entra tenant ID of the target user or channel; required for all proactive delivery lookups since `IConversationReferenceStore` keys on `(InternalUserId, TenantId)` or `(ChannelId, TenantId)`; populated by the orchestrator from the task's tenant context when creating the question), `TargetUserId` (string?, nullable — internal user ID of the intended recipient for proactive delivery; null when targeting a channel), `TargetChannelId` (string?, nullable — Teams channel ID for channel-scoped questions; null when targeting a specific user; exactly one of `TargetUserId` or `TargetChannelId` must be non-null — `TeamsMessengerConnector` resolves the populated field together with `TenantId` to a `ConversationReference` via `IConversationReferenceStore`), `Title` (string), `Body` (string), `Severity` (string — `Info`, `Warning`, `Error`, `Critical`), `AllowedActions` (IReadOnlyList&lt;HumanAction&gt;), `ExpiresAt` (DateTimeOffset), `ConversationId` (string?, nullable — the Teams conversation ID where the question was delivered; null on creation; populated at card-send time by `SendQuestionAsync` or `TeamsProactiveNotifier` with the conversation ID from the active turn context; persisted in the `AgentQuestions` SQL table in Stage 3.3; used by `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` for bare `approve`/`reject` text command resolution per `architecture.md` §2.5 lines 133-134), `CorrelationId` (string), `CreatedAt` (DateTimeOffset — UTC timestamp of question creation; set to `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow` by `IAgentQuestionStore.SaveAsync` on first save; required by `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` for ordering results by creation time and by `GetOpenExpiredAsync` for batch-scanning expired questions; persisted in the `AgentQuestions` SQL table `CreatedAt` column in Stage 3.3), `Status` (string — `Open`, `Resolved`, `Expired`; default `Open` on creation; transitions: `Open` → `Resolved` when a human decision is recorded via `CardActionHandler` or text `approve`/`reject`; `Open` → `Expired` when `QuestionExpiryProcessor` detects `ExpiresAt < UtcNow`; transitions are atomic via `IAgentQuestionStore.TryUpdateStatusAsync` with compare-and-set semantics; this field is persisted in the `AgentQuestions` SQL table in Stage 3.3 and checked by `CardActionHandler` to enforce first-writer-wins idempotency). Aligned with `architecture.md` §AgentQuestion field table lines 277-289 and `e2e-scenarios.md` §Proactive Blocking Question lines 85-95.
- [ ] Define `HumanAction` record with fields: `ActionId`, `Label`, `Value`, `RequiresComment`.
- [ ] Define `HumanDecisionEvent` record with fields: `QuestionId`, `ActionValue`, `Comment`, `Messenger`, `ExternalUserId`, `ExternalMessageId`, `ReceivedAt`, `CorrelationId`.
- [ ] Define `MessengerEvent` base record with fields: `EventType` (string — discriminator from the canonical domain vocabulary: `AgentTaskRequest`, `Command`, `Escalation`, `PauseAgent`, `ResumeAgent`, `Decision`, `Text`, `InstallUpdate`, `Reaction`; aligned with `architecture.md` §3.1 cross-doc alignment note lines 360-362 and `e2e-scenarios.md` §Correlation and Traceability lines 723-728) and `Source` (string — origination channel: `PersonalChat`, `TeamChannel`, `MessageAction`; used by message-action handling in Stage 3.4 to tag events with `Source = MessageAction`). Define subtypes: `CommandEvent` (variable `EventType` based on parsed command — `AgentTaskRequest` for `agent ask`, `Command` for general commands, `Escalation`/`PauseAgent`/`ResumeAgent` for lifecycle commands), `DecisionEvent` (with `EventType = "Decision"`), `TextEvent` (with `EventType = "Text"`).

### Dependencies
- _none — start stage_

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Serialize round-trip — Given an `AgentQuestion` with two `HumanAction` items, When serialized to JSON and deserialized, Then all field values match the original.
- [ ] Scenario: Required field validation — Given an `AgentQuestion` with null `QuestionId`, When validated, Then a validation error is returned.
- [ ] Scenario: Immutable records — Given a `HumanDecisionEvent`, When attempting to modify `QuestionId`, Then a compile-time error prevents mutation.

## Stage 1.2: Messenger Connector Interface

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Define `IMessengerConnector` interface with methods: `SendMessageAsync(MessengerMessage, CancellationToken)`, `SendQuestionAsync(AgentQuestion, CancellationToken)`, `ReceiveAsync(CancellationToken)`.
- [ ] Create project `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core` targeting .NET 8 and add it to the `AgentSwarm.Messaging.sln` solution (per `architecture.md` §7 lines 1142-1144 which assigns retry engine, rate limiter, deduplication, and outbox infrastructure to this assembly; and `tech-spec.md` §6.1 lines 225-227 which assigns retry/rate-limit/dedup/outbox infrastructure to `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core`). This project must exist before any files can be placed in it.
- [ ] Define `IMessageOutbox` interface in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core` (per `architecture.md` §4.4 lines 622-627 and `tech-spec.md` §6.1 lines 225-227 which assign outbox/retry/dedup infrastructure to `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core`) with methods: `EnqueueAsync`, `DequeueAsync`, `AcknowledgeAsync`, `DeadLetterAsync` for durable outbound messaging. Implement `NoOpMessageOutbox : IMessageOutbox` stub in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core` that logs dead-letter calls via `ILogger` and discards them (returns `Task.CompletedTask` for all methods). This stub is created here alongside the interface so it is available when Stage 2.1 registers it in DI. Stage 6.1 replaces the stub with `SqlMessageOutbox` via DI override.
- [ ] Define `ICommandDispatcher` interface with method `DispatchAsync(CommandContext context, CancellationToken ct)` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions`. This minimal contract allows the activity handler (Stage 2.2) to route parsed commands without depending on the concrete `CommandDispatcher` implementation (Stage 3.2).
- [ ] Define `IInboundEventPublisher` interface in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` with method `PublishAsync(MessengerEvent messengerEvent, CancellationToken ct)` that writes an inbound event to the shared in-process event channel for consumption by `IMessengerConnector.ReceiveAsync`. This contract decouples event producers (`TeamsSwarmActivityHandler`, `CommandDispatcher`, `CardActionHandler`) from the event consumer (`TeamsMessengerConnector.ReceiveAsync`). The default implementation `ChannelInboundEventPublisher` (created in Stage 2.1) uses `System.Threading.Channels.Channel<MessengerEvent>` as the backing transport — producers call `PublishAsync` to write to the channel writer, and `ReceiveAsync` reads from the channel reader. This explicit publisher contract and DI wiring addresses the inbound event handoff gap: `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` and `CommandDispatcher` inject `IInboundEventPublisher` to publish `CommandEvent` and `HumanDecisionEvent` records; `CardActionHandler` injects it to publish `DecisionEvent` records; `TeamsMessengerConnector.ReceiveAsync` reads from the channel's reader end.
- [ ] Define `IIdentityResolver` interface with method `ResolveAsync(string aadObjectId)` returning an internal user identity record, and `IUserAuthorizationService` interface with method `AuthorizeAsync(string tenantId, string userId, string command)` returning an authorization result, both in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` (interface assembly per `architecture.md` §2.17 Interface field: "defined in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions`; implementations in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams`", §2.18 Interface field: same split, and §7 assembly table row for `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` which explicitly lists `IIdentityResolver (interface)` and `IUserAuthorizationService (interface)`). Note: `architecture.md` §2.17/§2.18 Assembly field reads `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` — that refers to the concrete component assembly (`EntraIdentityResolver`, `RbacAuthorizationService`) listed in §7's `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` row, NOT the interface definition location. The interfaces live in Abstractions; the implementations live in Teams — consistent across both §2.17/§2.18 Interface fields, §4.9/§4.10 code comments, and §7. These minimal contracts allow Stage 2.2 to gate conversation reference capture on authorization without depending on the concrete RBAC implementation (Stage 5.1).
- [ ] Implement `DefaultDenyIdentityResolver : IIdentityResolver` stub in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` that returns `null` for all AAD object IDs (rejecting unmapped users immediately). Implement `DefaultDenyAuthorizationService : IUserAuthorizationService` stub in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` that returns `IsAuthorized = false` for all requests (enforcing a minimal deny-all policy). These stubs are created here in Stage 1.2 so they are available when Stage 2.1 registers them in DI (Stage 2.1 depends on this stage via Phase 2's dependency on Phase 1). Stage 2.2's `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` injects and calls these interfaces before the full RBAC implementations exist (Stage 5.1 replaces them via DI override).
- [ ] Define `IAgentQuestionStore` interface in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions` with core CRUD methods: `SaveAsync(AgentQuestion question, CancellationToken ct)`, `GetByIdAsync(string questionId, CancellationToken ct)` returning the full `AgentQuestion` with all fields including `AllowedActions` and `Status`, `TryUpdateStatusAsync(string questionId, string expectedStatus, string newStatus, CancellationToken ct)` returning `bool` — atomically transitions `Status` from `expectedStatus` to `newStatus` using compare-and-set semantics; returns `true` if the transition succeeded, `false` if the current status did not match `expectedStatus` (per `architecture.md` §6.3 lines 955-957), and `UpdateConversationIdAsync(string questionId, string conversationId, CancellationToken ct)` — sets the `ConversationId` field on a previously saved `AgentQuestion`; called by `SendQuestionAsync` (Stage 2.3) and `TeamsProactiveNotifier` (Stage 4.2) after the proactive send completes. The concrete implementation backed by a SQL table is provided in Stage 3.3.
- [ ] Add query methods to `IAgentQuestionStore` interface: `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync(string conversationId, CancellationToken ct)` returning `AgentQuestion?` — queries for the most recently created question with `Status = "Open"` and a matching `ConversationId`, ordered by `CreatedAt` descending (per `architecture.md` §2.5 lines 133-134); `GetOpenByConversationAsync(string conversationId, CancellationToken ct)` returning `IReadOnlyList<AgentQuestion>` — queries for ALL open questions with a matching `ConversationId`, ordered by `CreatedAt` descending, used by `ApproveCommandHandler` and `RejectCommandHandler` (Stage 3.2) for bare approve/reject disambiguation; `GetOpenExpiredAsync(DateTimeOffset cutoff, int batchSize, CancellationToken ct)` returning `IReadOnlyList<AgentQuestion>` — queries for up to `batchSize` questions where `Status = "Open"` and `ExpiresAt < cutoff`, used by `QuestionExpiryProcessor` (Stage 3.3).
- [ ] Define `ConnectorOptions` base class with common config: `RetryCount`, `RetryDelayMs`, `MaxConcurrency`, `DeadLetterThreshold`.

### Dependencies
- phase-messaging-abstractions-and-data-model/stage-core-data-models

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Interface contract completeness — Given the `IMessengerConnector` interface, When inspected via reflection, Then it contains exactly `SendMessageAsync`, `SendQuestionAsync`, and `ReceiveAsync` methods.
- [ ] Scenario: Options defaults — Given a default `ConnectorOptions`, When instantiated, Then `RetryCount` is 3 and `RetryDelayMs` is 1000.

## Stage 1.3: Persistence Abstractions

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create project `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Persistence` targeting .NET 8.
- [ ] Define `IAuditLogger` interface with method `LogAsync(AuditEntry, CancellationToken)` where `AuditEntry` includes all canonical fields from `tech-spec.md` §4.3 (Canonical Audit Record Schema): `Timestamp` (DateTimeOffset), `CorrelationId` (string), `EventType` (string — exactly seven canonical values: `CommandReceived`, `MessageSent`, `CardActionReceived`, `SecurityRejection`, `ProactiveNotification`, `MessageActionReceived`, `Error`; message actions (Teams message-extension submissions) log as `MessageActionReceived` — a dedicated audit event type distinct from `CommandReceived` — because message-action submissions arrive through the `composeExtension/submitAction` invoke mechanism rather than direct text commands, and distinguishing them in the audit trail supports compliance filtering and forensic analysis; the `Source` field on the domain `MessengerEvent` additionally marks the origination for downstream processing, per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 Canonical Audit Record Schema), `ActorId` (string — AAD object ID for users, agent ID for agents), `ActorType` (string — `User` or `Agent`), `TenantId` (string), `AgentId` (string, optional — the agent whose task or question triggered this event; present on all events tied to an agent task including human-originated actions such as `approve` or `reject`; null for events not associated with a specific agent such as `agent status` queries or security rejections; per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 lines 139 and 146 which make `AgentId` a first-class canonical audit field), `TaskId` (string, optional), `ConversationId` (string, optional), `Action` (string), `PayloadJson` (string — sanitized JSON payload), `Outcome` (string — `Success`, `Rejected`, `Failed`, `DeadLettered`).
- [ ] Define `IMessageStore` interface for persisting inbound/outbound messages with methods: `SaveInboundAsync`, `SaveOutboundAsync`, `GetByCorrelationIdAsync`.
- [ ] Implement `AuditEntry` as an immutable record with all canonical fields listed above (including `AgentId`) plus an implementation-specific `Checksum` field (SHA-256 of row content for tamper detection).
- [ ] Implement `NoOpAuditLogger : IAuditLogger` stub in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Persistence` that accepts all `LogAsync` calls as no-ops (returns `Task.CompletedTask`). This stub is created here alongside the `IAuditLogger` interface definition so it is available when Stage 2.1 registers it in DI. `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` (Stage 2.2) injects `IAuditLogger` as a required dependency — without this stub, the handler cannot be constructed before the concrete `SqlAuditLogger` lands in Stage 5.2. Stage 5.2 replaces the no-op stub with `SqlAuditLogger` via DI override.

### Dependencies
- phase-messaging-abstractions-and-data-model/stage-core-data-models

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Audit entry immutability — Given an `AuditEntry` record, When created, Then all properties are init-only and cannot be modified.
- [ ] Scenario: Correlation query contract — Given `IMessageStore`, When inspected, Then `GetByCorrelationIdAsync` accepts a `string correlationId` and returns a list of messages.

# Phase 2: Teams Bot Framework Core

## Dependencies
- phase-messaging-abstractions-and-data-model

## Stage 2.1: ASP.NET Core Bot Host

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create project `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` with NuGet references: `Microsoft.Bot.Builder` (4.22+) and `Microsoft.Bot.Builder.Integration.AspNet.Core` (4.22+). The `Microsoft.Bot.Builder` NuGet package ships all Teams support in two internal namespaces: `Microsoft.Bot.Builder.Teams` (which contains `TeamsActivityHandler`, Teams middleware, and helper methods) and `Microsoft.Bot.Schema.Teams` (which contains Teams-specific model types: `TeamsChannelData`, `TeamInfo`, `TeamsChannelAccount`). No separate Teams NuGet package is required (per `tech-spec.md` §2.1 line 34 and §6.2 line 235). The legacy `Microsoft.Bot.Connector.Teams` NuGet package (max published version 4.3.0-beta1) is **not used** — it predates Bot Framework SDK v4 GA and all its functionality was folded into `Microsoft.Bot.Builder`. Add the project to `AgentSwarm.Messaging.sln`. The concrete `SqlCardStateStore` also co-locates in this project. The next two steps create all Teams-specific interface and type files in this project.
- [ ] Create `IConversationReferenceStore.cs`, `ICardActionHandler.cs`, and `ITeamsCardLifecycleService.cs` interface files in the `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` project. `IConversationReferenceStore` defines the full method surface: `SaveOrUpdateAsync`, `GetAsync`, `GetAllActiveAsync`, `GetByAadObjectIdAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)` (lookup by Teams-native AAD identity key), `GetByInternalUserIdAsync(string tenantId, string internalUserId)` (lookup by orchestrator identity key for proactive routing), `GetByChannelIdAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)`, `MarkInactiveAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)` (user-scoped uninstall), `MarkInactiveByChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)` (channel-scoped uninstall per `architecture.md` §4.2 lines 543-544), `IsActiveAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)`, `DeleteAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)`, `DeleteByChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)` (administrative cleanup only). The dual-key model (separate `AadObjectId` and `InternalUserId` fields per `architecture.md` §TeamsConversationReference lines 383-384) supports two lookup paths. `ICardActionHandler` defines `HandleAsync(ITurnContext turnContext, CancellationToken ct)` returning `AdaptiveCardInvokeResponse` (uses Bot Framework types, hence placed in Teams not Abstractions). `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` defines `UpdateCardToResolvedAsync(string questionId, string resolvedByUserId, string actionValue, CancellationToken ct)` and `DeleteCardAsync(string questionId, CancellationToken ct)` — the SOLE call path for card update/delete operations.
- [ ] Create `TeamsCardState.cs` record and `ICardStateStore.cs` interface in the `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` project (co-located to avoid a circular Abstractions → Teams assembly dependency since `ICardStateStore.SaveAsync` takes `TeamsCardState` as a parameter). `TeamsCardState` record has fields: `QuestionId` (string), `ActivityId` (string — Teams message ID), `ConversationId` (string), `ConversationReferenceJson` (string — serialized `ConversationReference` for background rehydration), `Status` (string — `Pending`/`Answered`/`Expired`), `CreatedAt` (DateTimeOffset), `UpdatedAt` (DateTimeOffset). `ICardStateStore` interface defines: `SaveAsync(TeamsCardState, CancellationToken)`, `GetByQuestionIdAsync(string questionId, CancellationToken)` returning the full `TeamsCardState` including `ConversationReferenceJson`, `UpdateStatusAsync(string questionId, string newStatus, CancellationToken)`. **Assembly source-of-truth**: this implementation plan places `ICardStateStore` and `TeamsCardState` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` — this is the canonical assembly assignment. `architecture.md` §4.3 line 614 lists `ICardStateStore` under `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Abstractions`; that reference is stale and should be updated to `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` in the next architecture.md iteration to align with this plan's co-location decision.
- [ ] Create project `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Worker` as an ASP.NET Core worker service host (per `architecture.md` §7 line 1146 and `e2e-scenarios.md` lines 19, 142 which reference `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Worker` as the running host). This project references `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` and `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Core`, and contains the `Program.cs`/`Startup` configuration, DI registration, health check endpoints, and OpenTelemetry setup. The `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` project contains only Teams-specific connector logic (middleware, activity handler, connector); the Worker project is the composable host that wires everything together. Add the project to `AgentSwarm.Messaging.sln`.
- [ ] Create `TeamsMessagingOptions` configuration class with properties: `MicrosoftAppId`, `MicrosoftAppPassword`, `MicrosoftAppTenantId`, `AllowedTenantIds` (list), `BotEndpoint`, `RateLimitPerTenantPerMinute` (int, default 100), `DeduplicationTtlMinutes` (int, default 10), `MaxRetryAttempts` (int, default 5), `RetryBaseDelaySeconds` (int, default 2). The `MaxRetryAttempts` and `RetryBaseDelaySeconds` properties override the base-class `ConnectorOptions` defaults (`RetryCount = 3`, `RetryDelayMs = 1000`) with Teams-specific canonical values per `tech-spec.md` §4.4.
- [ ] Implement `TenantValidationMiddleware` as an **ASP.NET Core middleware** (not Bot Framework `IMiddleware`) in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Middleware` — an HTTP-layer middleware that runs in the ASP.NET Core request pipeline BEFORE `CloudAdapter` processes the request (registered in `Program.cs` via `app.UseMiddleware<TenantValidationMiddleware>()` before `app.MapControllers()`). It reads the `AllowedTenantIds` list from `TeamsMessagingOptions` (via `IOptions<TeamsMessagingOptions>`), reads the raw HTTP request body (buffering with `EnableBuffering()` so `CloudAdapter` can re-read it), deserializes the `Activity` JSON to extract `ChannelData.tenant.id` (or `Conversation.TenantId`), and rejects activities from tenants not in the list by setting **HTTP 403 Forbidden** on the ASP.NET Core response and short-circuiting the pipeline (does NOT call `next()`) — **no bot response, no Adaptive Card, no reply of any kind** is sent to blocked tenants (per `tech-spec.md` §4.2 row 2 which specifies tenant allow-list failures are rejected at the HTTP middleware layer before the request reaches `CloudAdapter`). This design gives the middleware direct control over HTTP status codes — Bot Framework `IMiddleware` (which runs inside `CloudAdapter`) cannot set HTTP status codes because `CloudAdapter.ProcessAsync` always returns HTTP 200 for processed activities. Log a structured warning via `ILogger` for blocked tenants. Note on audit logging: this stage adds only basic `ILogger` structured logging for operational visibility; Stage 5.1 later enhances this same middleware with formal `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` compliance-grade audit logging (emitting a `SecurityRejection` audit entry). Only ONE audit record is emitted per blocked tenant request — Stage 5.1 replaces the `ILogger` warning with an `IAuditLogger` call, it does not add a second logging path.
- [ ] Implement `TelemetryMiddleware : IMiddleware` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Middleware` that records OpenTelemetry spans for every inbound activity with attributes: `activity.type`, `activity.id`, `tenant.id`, `conversation.id`, and `correlation.id`. Configure via `TelemetryMiddlewareOptions` (injectable) with `bool EnableDetailedPayloadCapture` (default `false`) and `string[] SensitiveActivityTypes` (default empty — types for which payload is redacted). Register the middleware as a singleton in DI.
- [ ] Define `IActivityIdStore` interface in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` with method `Task<bool> IsSeenOrMarkAsync(string activityId, CancellationToken ct)` — returns `true` if the activity ID was already seen (duplicate), otherwise atomically marks it as seen with a configurable TTL. Aligned with `architecture.md` §4.8 lines 626-637. Implement `InMemoryActivityIdStore : IActivityIdStore` using a `ConcurrentDictionary<string, DateTimeOffset>` with a background eviction timer (TTL: 10 minutes from `TeamsMessagingOptions.DeduplicationTtlMinutes`). This default implementation is sufficient for single-instance deployments; multi-instance deployments can swap in a Redis-backed implementation. Register `InMemoryActivityIdStore` as `IActivityIdStore` singleton in DI (in the `Startup`/`Program.cs` step below).
- [ ] Implement `ActivityDeduplicationMiddleware : IMiddleware` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Middleware` that suppresses duplicate inbound webhook deliveries by checking `Activity.Id` (or `Activity.ReplyToId` for invoke activities) against the injected `IActivityIdStore`. Use a configurable TTL (default: 10 minutes from `TeamsMessagingOptions.DeduplicationTtlMinutes`, aligned with `architecture.md` §2.16 `IActivityIdStore` default TTL). Short-circuit duplicates with HTTP 200 and log a deduplication event. This is distinct from Stage 6.2's domain-level idempotency check which operates on `(QuestionId, UserId)` pairs in `CardActionHandler`.
- [ ] Implement `RateLimitMiddleware : IMiddleware` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Middleware` that applies per-tenant inbound rate limiting using a sliding-window counter. Read `RateLimitPerTenantPerMinute` from `TeamsMessagingOptions` (default: 100 activities per minute per tenant). Maintain per-tenant counters in a `ConcurrentDictionary<string, SlidingWindowCounter>` with 1-minute windows. When the rate limit is exceeded, short-circuit with HTTP 429 and a `Retry-After` header calculated from the window remaining time. Log a rate-limit event for monitoring. Register the middleware as a singleton in DI.
- [ ] Implement `Program.cs` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Worker` (the ASP.NET Core host project created earlier in this stage; per `architecture.md` §7 line 1146 and `e2e-scenarios.md` lines 19, 142) with ASP.NET Core host builder, controller discovery via `builder.Services.AddControllers().AddApplicationPart(typeof(TeamsWebhookController).Assembly)`, health check endpoints (`/health`, `/ready`), and OpenTelemetry tracing configuration. Bind `TeamsMessagingOptions` from configuration (see options registration step below).
- [ ] Register `CloudAdapter` (from `Microsoft.Bot.Builder.Integration.AspNet.Core`) as the bot adapter in `Program.cs` with the Bot Framework `IMiddleware` pipeline in this exact order: `TelemetryMiddleware` → `ActivityDeduplicationMiddleware` → `RateLimitMiddleware`. This is a three-middleware Bot Framework pipeline — `TenantValidationMiddleware` is NOT in this pipeline because it runs as an ASP.NET Core HTTP middleware BEFORE `CloudAdapter` (see the `TenantValidationMiddleware` step above), giving it direct control over HTTP status codes (e.g., HTTP 403 for blocked tenants). The ASP.NET Core middleware pipeline order is: `TenantValidationMiddleware` (HTTP layer, sets 403) → `CloudAdapter.ProcessAsync` → Bot Framework pipeline (`TelemetryMiddleware` → `ActivityDeduplicationMiddleware` → `RateLimitMiddleware`). All three Bot Framework middleware classes are `IMiddleware` implementations created in the preceding steps within this stage (in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams`); the Worker project references `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` to access them. Register `IBot` pointing to `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler`.
- [ ] Register conversation reference and identity stubs in DI (`Program.cs` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Worker`): `InMemoryConversationReferenceStore` as `IConversationReferenceStore` — a `ConcurrentDictionary`-backed in-memory implementation created in this step (sufficient for local dev and integration tests; replaced by `SqlConversationReferenceStore` in Stage 4.1); `DefaultDenyIdentityResolver` as `IIdentityResolver` and `DefaultDenyAuthorizationService` as `IUserAuthorizationService` (both created in Stage 1.2; replaced by full RBAC implementations in Stage 5.1).
- [ ] Register command dispatcher and question store stubs in DI: a no-op `ICommandDispatcher` stub that returns a "commands not yet available" reply (replaced by concrete `CommandDispatcher` in Stage 3.2); `InMemoryAgentQuestionStore` as `IAgentQuestionStore` — backed by a `ConcurrentDictionary<string, AgentQuestion>` that supports `SaveAsync` (stores keyed by `QuestionId`), `GetByIdAsync` (lookup by key), `TryUpdateStatusAsync` (compare-and-set using `Interlocked` semantics), `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` (LINQ scan filtered by `ConversationId` and `Status = "Open"`, ordered by `CreatedAt` descending), `UpdateConversationIdAsync` (updates `ConversationId` field), and `GetOpenExpiredAsync` (LINQ scan filtered by `Status = "Open"` and `ExpiresAt < cutoff`, ordered ascending, limited by `batchSize`), and `GetOpenByConversationAsync` (LINQ scan filtered by `ConversationId` and `Status = "Open"`, ordered by `CreatedAt` descending, returning the full list). This in-memory stub is sufficient for Stage 2.3 and Stage 2.2 before the SQL-backed `SqlAgentQuestionStore` lands in Stage 3.3.
- [ ] Register card-related stubs in DI: `NoOpCardStateStore` as `ICardStateStore` — an in-memory stub using `ConcurrentDictionary` (replaced by `SqlCardStateStore` in Stage 3.3); `NoOpCardActionHandler` as `ICardActionHandler` — returns a "card actions not yet available" `AdaptiveCardInvokeResponse` (replaced by `CardActionHandler` in Stage 3.3); `NoOpCardLifecycleService` as `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` — logs and no-ops (replaced by `TeamsCardLifecycleService` in Stage 3.3).
- [ ] Register infrastructure stubs in DI: `InMemoryActivityIdStore` as `IActivityIdStore` (created earlier in this stage); `ChannelInboundEventPublisher` as `IInboundEventPublisher` — a `System.Threading.Channels.Channel<MessengerEvent>`-backed implementation created in this step (unbounded channel connecting event producers to `TeamsMessengerConnector.ReceiveAsync`); `NoOpAuditLogger` as `IAuditLogger` (created in Stage 1.3; replaced by `SqlAuditLogger` in Stage 5.2); `NoOpMessageOutbox` as `IMessageOutbox` (created in Stage 1.2; replaced by `SqlMessageOutbox` in Stage 6.1).
- [ ] Create `TeamsWebhookController` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Controllers` (per `architecture.md` §2.2 lines 87-95 which defines `TeamsWebhookController` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams` with namespace `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Controllers`, and §7 line 1145 which lists `TeamsWebhookController` under the Teams connector assembly) with POST endpoint at `/api/messages` that delegates to `CloudAdapter.ProcessAsync`. The Worker project's `Program.cs` references this controller from the Teams assembly via `builder.Services.AddControllers().AddApplicationPart(typeof(TeamsWebhookController).Assembly)` to discover it at runtime.
- [ ] Register `TeamsMessagingOptions` from `appsettings.json` and environment variables using the Options pattern with `IValidateOptions<TeamsMessagingOptions>` to fail startup on missing required fields.

### Dependencies
- phase-messaging-abstractions-and-data-model/stage-messenger-connector-interface

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Bot endpoint responds — Given the bot host is running, When a POST is sent to `/api/messages` with a valid Bot Framework activity, Then it returns HTTP 200.
- [ ] Scenario: Health check — Given the bot host is running, When GET `/health` is called, Then it returns HTTP 200 with status `Healthy`.
- [ ] Scenario: Missing config fails startup — Given `MicrosoftAppId` is not configured, When the host starts, Then it throws `OptionsValidationException`.

## Stage 2.2: Teams Activity Handler

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` extending `TeamsActivityHandler`. The handler's constructor accepts ALL NINE of the following dependencies (each injected via DI and stored as a `readonly` field): (1) `IConversationReferenceStore` — persists/retrieves conversation references for proactive messaging; (2) `ICommandDispatcher` — routes parsed commands to handlers (interface in Stage 1.2; no-op stub registered in Stage 2.1; concrete `CommandDispatcher` in Stage 3.2); (3) `IIdentityResolver` — maps AAD object IDs to internal user identities (interface in Stage 1.2; `DefaultDenyIdentityResolver` stub in Stage 2.1; `EntraIdentityResolver` in Stage 5.1); (4) `IUserAuthorizationService` — enforces RBAC for command execution (interface in Stage 1.2; `DefaultDenyAuthorizationService` stub in Stage 2.1; `RbacAuthorizationService` in Stage 5.1); (5) `IAgentQuestionStore` — resolves originating questions and validates allowed actions in `OnAdaptiveCardInvokeAsync` (interface in Stage 1.2; no-op stub in Stage 2.1; `SqlAgentQuestionStore` in Stage 3.3); (6) `IAuditLogger` — emits compliance-grade audit entries (interface in Stage 1.3; `NoOpAuditLogger` stub registered in Stage 2.1; `SqlAuditLogger` in Stage 5.2); (7) `ICardActionHandler` — processes Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` invoke activities (interface defined in Stage 2.1; `NoOpCardActionHandler` stub registered in Stage 2.1; concrete `CardActionHandler : ICardActionHandler` in Stage 3.3); (8) `IInboundEventPublisher` — publishes inbound `MessengerEvent` records (including `CommandEvent` and `DecisionEvent` subtypes) to the shared in-process event channel for consumption by `TeamsMessengerConnector.ReceiveAsync` (interface in Stage 1.2; `ChannelInboundEventPublisher` backed by `System.Threading.Channels.Channel<MessengerEvent>` in Stage 2.1); (9) `ILogger<TeamsSwarmActivityHandler>` — structured operational logging. All nine are required for the handler to compile and function.
- [ ] Override `OnMessageActivityAsync` to strip `@mention` markup from incoming message text before dispatching: use `Activity.RemoveMentionText(Activity.Recipient.Id)` (or equivalent `TurnContext.Activity` helper) to normalize channel messages where Teams prepends `@AgentBot` to the text. This is the SOLE location for `@mention` stripping — `CommandDispatcher` (Stage 3.2) receives already-cleaned text and does NOT perform any mention stripping itself. This ensures command parsing works identically in personal chat and team channels (per `e2e-scenarios.md` §Personal Chat — Agent Task Creation lines 35-41 which require stripping `@AgentBot` before parsing in the team channel mention scenario). After normalization, route the cleaned text to the injected `ICommandDispatcher` (interface defined in Stage 1.2; concrete `CommandDispatcher` implementation is provided in Stage 3.2) via `ICommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync`, passing a `CommandContext` populated with the normalized text, the `TurnContext`, and the resolved user identity.
- [ ] In `OnMessageActivityAsync`, before dispatching the command, call the injected `IIdentityResolver.ResolveAsync` and `IUserAuthorizationService.AuthorizeAsync` (interfaces defined in Stage 1.2; default-deny stub implementations created in Stage 1.2 and registered in DI in Stage 2.1 — `DefaultDenyIdentityResolver` rejects unmapped users immediately and `DefaultDenyAuthorizationService` enforces a deny-all policy; Stage 5.1 replaces the stubs with full role-scoped RBAC implementations). After authorization succeeds, extract the `ConversationReference` from the incoming `Activity` via `Activity.GetConversationReference()` and call `IConversationReferenceStore.SaveOrUpdateAsync` to persist or update it. This ensures conversation references are captured only for authorized users on first message interaction (not for unauthorized or unmapped users), satisfying the story requirement that references are stored for authorized users/channels. This also satisfies `e2e-scenarios.md` §Conversation Reference Persistence scenario "Conversation reference is stored on first interaction" (lines 252-256).
- [ ] Override `OnTeamsMembersAddedAsync` to capture and persist the conversation reference on bot installation. **Authorization model for install events (deliberate two-tier design):** Install lifecycle events (`OnTeamsMembersAddedAsync`, `OnInstallationUpdateActivityAsync`) are app-level events, not user commands. They are subject to tenant validation only (enforced by `TenantValidationMiddleware` in the ASP.NET Core HTTP pipeline, which runs before `CloudAdapter` and before any handler — see Stage 2.1). They are NOT subject to user-level identity resolution (`IIdentityResolver`) or user-level authorization (`IUserAuthorizationService`). Rationale: (a) install events establish the bot's ability to send proactive messages to a conversation scope — they do not execute privileged commands; (b) the `Activity.From` on install events is the installing user, who may not yet have an identity mapping — requiring identity resolution at install time would prevent the bot from ever acquiring a conversation reference for new users; (c) user-level auth gates command execution in `OnMessageActivityAsync` — any subsequent command from an unauthorized user is rejected there, and the captured install reference is updated or superseded when an authorized user later sends a message and passes identity/auth checks. This two-tier design (tenant-only for install events, tenant + identity + RBAC for command events) is consistent across all install-related steps in this stage.
- [ ] Override `OnTeamsMembersRemovedAsync` to mark stored conversation references as inactive (retain for audit) on bot uninstall: for personal-scope uninstalls (bot removed by a single user), call `IConversationReferenceStore.MarkInactiveAsync(tenantId, aadObjectId)` keyed by the user's AAD object ID; for team-scope uninstalls (bot removed from a team), call `IConversationReferenceStore.MarkInactiveByChannelAsync(tenantId, channelId)` for each channel in the team to mark channel references inactive (per `architecture.md` §4.2 lines 543-544). Do not delete references — they are retained as inactive for audit.
- [ ] Override `OnInstallationUpdateActivityAsync` to handle Teams app install/uninstall lifecycle and log audit entries. On install, capture and persist the conversation reference (subject to tenant validation only — same two-tier authorization model described in the `OnTeamsMembersAddedAsync` step above: install events require tenant validation but NOT user-level identity/authorization gating; see that step for full rationale). On uninstall, mark conversation references inactive rather than removing them.
- [ ] Override `OnAdaptiveCardInvokeAsync` to delegate all Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` invoke activities to the injected `ICardActionHandler` (dependency #7 in the constructor above; `NoOpCardActionHandler` stub registered in Stage 2.1 returns a "card actions not yet available" response; concrete `CardActionHandler : ICardActionHandler` created in Stage 3.3). The concrete `CardActionHandler` owns the full card-action processing pipeline: extracting `ActionId` and optional comment from `Activity.Value`, resolving the originating `AgentQuestion` via `IAgentQuestionStore.GetByIdAsync(questionId)`, validating `AllowedActions`, producing a `HumanDecisionEvent`, and returning an `AdaptiveCardInvokeResponse`.
- [ ] Implement `OnTurnAsync` to add `CorrelationId` (from activity or new GUID) to the turn context for distributed tracing.

### Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core/stage-asp-net-core-bot-host

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Command routing— Given a message activity with text `agent ask create e2e test scenarios for update service`, When processed by `OnMessageActivityAsync`, Then the command dispatcher receives an `AskCommand` with prompt `create e2e test scenarios for update service`.
- [ ] Scenario: Bot install captures reference — Given a `MembersAdded` activity where the bot is added, When processed, Then the conversation reference is persisted via `IConversationReferenceStore.SaveOrUpdateAsync`.
- [ ] Scenario: Correlation ID propagation — Given an incoming activity without a `CorrelationId` header, When `OnTurnAsync` runs, Then a new GUID-based `CorrelationId` is attached to the turn context.
- [ ] Scenario: First interaction saves reference after auth — Given user `dave@contoso.com` has never interacted with the bot before and is identity-resolved and authorized, When `dave` sends `agent status` in personal chat, Then `OnMessageActivityAsync` extracts the conversation reference from the activity and calls `IConversationReferenceStore.SaveOrUpdateAsync`, persisting the reference keyed by `(AadObjectId, TenantId)` with `InternalUserId` populated from identity resolution, after confirming authorization.
- [ ] Scenario: Unauthorized user reference not persisted — Given user `eve@external.com` is not identity-mapped, When `eve` sends `agent ask something` in personal chat, Then `OnMessageActivityAsync` rejects the request with an access-denied card and does NOT call `IConversationReferenceStore.SaveOrUpdateAsync`.
- [ ] Scenario: @mention stripped in channel — Given a team channel message with text `<at>AgentBot</at> agent ask plan migration`, When `OnMessageActivityAsync` processes the activity, Then the `@AgentBot` mention markup is stripped and `CommandDispatcher` receives `agent ask plan migration`.

## Stage 2.3: Teams Messenger Connector

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Implement `TeamsMessengerConnector : IMessengerConnector`. The constructor accepts ALL FIVE of the following dependencies (each injected via DI): (1) `CloudAdapter` — the Bot Framework adapter for proactive sends; (2) `TeamsMessagingOptions` — configuration for app ID, tenant list, rate limits; (3) `IConversationReferenceStore` — resolves conversation references for targeted delivery; (4) `IAgentQuestionStore` — persists `AgentQuestion` records before proactive delivery (interface defined in Stage 1.2; no-op stub registered in Stage 2.1; concrete `SqlAgentQuestionStore` in Stage 3.3); (5) `ICardStateStore` — persists the mapping of `QuestionId` → Teams `ActivityId` for card update/delete operations (interface defined in Stage 2.1; `NoOpCardStateStore` stub registered in Stage 2.1; concrete SQL-backed implementation in Stage 3.3). `ICardStateStore` is required because `SendQuestionAsync` calls `ICardStateStore.SaveAsync` to persist the `ResourceResponse.Id` returned by `SendActivityAsync` so that proactive approval cards can be updated or deleted later. `IAgentQuestionStore` is required because `SendQuestionAsync` calls `IAgentQuestionStore.SaveAsync` to persist the question before sending — without these dependencies the class will not compile.
- [ ] Implement `SendMessageAsync` to send a text message to the stored conversation reference using `adapter.ContinueConversationAsync`.
- [ ] Implement `SendQuestionAsync` using a two-step persistence pattern: (1) persist the `AgentQuestion` to `IAgentQuestionStore.SaveAsync` (interface defined in Stage 1.2; concrete implementation in Stage 3.3) with `ConversationId` initially null (the Teams conversation ID is not yet known before the proactive send), then (2) render the question as a simple text summary and send proactively via `ContinueConversationAsync` using `TargetUserId` or `TargetChannelId` to resolve the correct conversation reference from `IConversationReferenceStore`, then (3) after the send completes, call `IAgentQuestionStore.UpdateConversationIdAsync(question.QuestionId, turnContext.Activity.Conversation.Id, ct)` to populate the `ConversationId` on the persisted question with the actual Teams conversation ID from the proactive turn context — this enables `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` to find this question for bare `approve`/`reject` text commands. Adaptive Card rendering is wired in Phase 3 Stage 3.1 when `AdaptiveCardBuilder` becomes available.
- [ ] Implement `ReceiveAsync` to read from the `System.Threading.Channels.Channel<MessengerEvent>` backing the injected `IInboundEventPublisher` (interface defined in Stage 1.2). The `ChannelInboundEventPublisher` implementation (registered in Stage 2.1) exposes both a `ChannelWriter<MessengerEvent>` (used by `PublishAsync`) and a `ChannelReader<MessengerEvent>` (used by `ReceiveAsync`). Event producers — `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler`, `CommandDispatcher`, `CardActionHandler` — write to the channel via `IInboundEventPublisher.PublishAsync`; `ReceiveAsync` reads from the channel reader, completing the inbound event handoff contract.
- [ ] Wire `TeamsMessengerConnector` into DI as `IMessengerConnector` keyed by `"teams"`.

### Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core/stage-teams-activity-handler

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Send message to stored reference — Given a valid conversation reference in the store, When `SendMessageAsync` is called, Then `ContinueConversationAsync` is invoked with the correct reference.
- [ ] Scenario: Receive command event — Given the activity handler processes an `agent status` message, When `ReceiveAsync` is awaited, Then a `CommandEvent` with `Command = "status"` is returned.
- [ ] Scenario: Send with missing reference — Given no conversation reference exists for the target user, When `SendMessageAsync` is called, Then an `InvalidOperationException` is thrown with a descriptive message.

## Stage 2.4: Teams App Manifest

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create Teams app manifest `manifest.json` conforming to manifest schema v1.16+ with `$schema`, `manifestVersion`, `id` (bot's AAD app ID), `version`, `name`, `description`, and `developer` fields.
- [ ] Configure bot capability in manifest with `botId` referencing the `MicrosoftAppId`, `scopes` set to `["personal", "team"]`, and `supportsFiles: false`.
- [ ] Add message extension (compose extension) entry in manifest with `type: "action"`, `commandId`, `title`, and `context: ["message", "commandBox"]` to support forwarding message context to agents. This manifest entry declares a complete action command definition with all required fields (`id`, `title`, `description`, `type: "action"`, `fetchTask: false`) so the extension is recognized by Teams immediately upon sideloading. The manifest entry is fully functional as a declaration — Teams will route `composeExtension/submitAction` invocations to the bot endpoint as soon as the manifest is installed. Stage 3.4 implements the server-side `MessageExtensionHandler` and `OnTeamsMessagingExtensionSubmitActionAsync` that processes those invocations (per `tech-spec.md` §2.1 line 39: message-extension action commands are fully functional). Stage 3.4 updates any additional manifest fields if the handler requires them.
- [ ] Add `validDomains` for the bot endpoint and `webApplicationInfo` with `id` (AAD app ID) and `resource` (API URI) for SSO support.
- [ ] Create `manifest.zip` packaging script that bundles `manifest.json`, `color.png` (192×192), and `outline.png` (32×32) icons for sideloading or admin deployment.

### Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core/stage-asp-net-core-bot-host

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Manifest schema validation— Given the generated `manifest.json`, When validated against the Teams manifest schema v1.16, Then no schema errors are reported.
- [ ] Scenario: Required scopes present — Given the manifest, When the `bots[0].scopes` field is inspected, Then it contains both `personal` and `team`.
- [ ] Scenario: Message extension entry present — Given the manifest, When the `composeExtensions` field is inspected, Then it contains at least one action command entry with all required fields (`id`, `title`, `description`, `type: "action"`, `fetchTask: false`).

# Phase 3: Adaptive Cards and Command Processing

## Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core

## Stage 3.1: Adaptive Card Templates

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `AdaptiveCardBuilder` service that renders `AgentQuestion` to an Adaptive Card JSON using the AdaptiveCards NuGet package.
- [ ] Implement approval card template with: title, body text, severity indicator, action buttons generated from `HumanAction` list, optional comment input for actions where `RequiresComment = true`.
- [ ] Implement status summary card template showing: agent ID, task ID, current status, last update timestamp, progress percentage.
- [ ] Implement incident escalation card template with: severity level, affected agents, incident summary, escalate/acknowledge buttons.
- [ ] Implement release gate card template with: gate name, release version, environment, gate conditions checklist, approve/reject/defer buttons, and gate status indicator. **Multi-approver modeling**: release gates requiring multiple approvers are NOT modeled as a single shared `AgentQuestion` with a threshold counter. Instead, the orchestrator creates **separate `AgentQuestion` records — one per required approver** — each following the standard single-decision first-writer-wins lifecycle (per `architecture.md` §6.3.1 lines 965-978 and `e2e-scenarios.md` §Release gate approval with multiple approvers lines 773-791). Each per-approver `AgentQuestion` has its own `QuestionId`, `TargetUserId` set to the individual approver, and independent `Open → Resolved` lifecycle. The release gate card template renders identically for each approver; threshold aggregation (e.g., "2 of 3 approvers must approve") is handled by the orchestrator's workflow layer, NOT by `CardActionHandler` or the card template. This step creates the card template only — Stage 3.3's `CardActionHandler` processes each approver's card action independently.
- [ ] Create `CardActionMapper` to map Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` data payloads back to `HumanDecisionEvent` records.
- [ ] Refactor `TeamsMessengerConnector.SendQuestionAsync` (Stage 2.3) to use `AdaptiveCardBuilder` for rendering proactive questions as Adaptive Cards instead of the interim text summary. Inject `AdaptiveCardBuilder` into `TeamsMessengerConnector` as a new constructor dependency. The method now calls `AdaptiveCardBuilder.RenderQuestion(agentQuestion)` to produce the Adaptive Card JSON, wraps it in an `Attachment`, and sends it via `ContinueConversationAsync`. This completes the acceptance criterion for proactive Adaptive Card questions: agents can proactively send blocking questions rendered as interactive Adaptive Cards with action buttons. Note: `TeamsProactiveNotifier` (created in Stage 4.2) also uses `AdaptiveCardBuilder` — that wiring is handled in Stage 4.2's own implementation steps, which depend on this stage via Phase 4's dependency chain.

### Dependencies
- _none — start stage_

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Approval card rendering — Given an `AgentQuestion` with actions `Approve` and `Reject`, When rendered by `AdaptiveCardBuilder`, Then the resulting JSON contains two `Action.Submit` elements with matching labels.
- [ ] Scenario: Comment input conditional — Given a `HumanAction` with `RequiresComment = true`, When the card is rendered, Then an `Input.Text` field is included adjacent to the action button.
- [ ] Scenario: Card action round-trip — Given an Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` payload with `questionId`, `actionValue`, and `comment`, When mapped by `CardActionMapper`, Then the resulting `HumanDecisionEvent` has all fields correctly populated.

## Stage 3.2: Command Dispatcher

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `ICommandHandler` interface with `Task HandleAsync(CommandContext context, CancellationToken ct)` and a `string CommandName` property.
- [ ] Implement `AskCommandHandler` that creates a new agent task from user input text and sends acknowledgement.
- [ ] Implement `StatusCommandHandler` that queries the agent swarm orchestrator and returns a status summary card.
- [ ] Implement `ApproveCommandHandler` and `RejectCommandHandler` for text-based approval/rejection commands. **Command syntax**: `approve [questionId]` and `reject [questionId]` — the `questionId` argument is **optional**. Both forms are valid: (a) **explicit** — `approve q-123` or `reject q-456` — the handler resolves the question directly via `IAgentQuestionStore.GetByIdAsync(questionId)`; (b) **bare** — `approve` or `reject` with no argument — the handler falls back to a **per-conversation pending-question lookup** by calling `IAgentQuestionStore.GetOpenByConversationAsync(conversationId)` (defined on `IAgentQuestionStore` in Stage 1.2) to retrieve ALL open questions in the current conversation. Bare-command resolution: if the returned list has exactly one item, it is used as the target (auto-resolved without disambiguation); if zero are found, the handler replies with "no open questions in this conversation"; if more than one are found, the handler returns a disambiguation Adaptive Card listing each open question's `QuestionId`, `Title`, and `CreatedAt` so the user can re-issue the command with an explicit `questionId`. Once the target question is identified (by either path), the resolution contract is: (1) validate that the submitted action (`approve` or `reject`) is in `AllowedActions`; (2) atomically transition `Status` from `Open` to `Resolved` via `TryUpdateStatusAsync`; (3) emit a `HumanDecisionEvent`. This satisfies `architecture.md` §2.5 lines 133-134 which say bare `approve`/`reject` resolve the most recent pending approval in context (when exactly one is open).
- [ ] Implement `GetOpenByConversationAsync` in `ApproveCommandHandler` and `RejectCommandHandler` call sites: this method is already declared on the `IAgentQuestionStore` interface in Stage 1.2 (no interface change is needed here). This step wires the handler to call `IAgentQuestionStore.GetOpenByConversationAsync(conversationId)` when no explicit `questionId` argument is provided; the handler inspects the returned list count to determine single-target vs. disambiguation behavior. The concrete `SqlAgentQuestionStore` (Stage 3.3) implements this query against the `AgentQuestions` table using the filtered index on `(ConversationId, Status) WHERE Status = 'Open'`, ordered by `CreatedAt` descending, returning all matching rows.
- [ ] Implement `EscalateCommandHandler`, `PauseCommandHandler`, and `ResumeCommandHandler` for agent lifecycle management.
- [ ] Create `CommandDispatcher : ICommandDispatcher` that parses `CommandContext.NormalizedText` to identify the command keyword, resolves the matching `ICommandHandler` from DI, and dispatches with structured logging and correlation. **`CommandDispatcher` MUST NOT call `Activity.RemoveMentionText` or perform any `@mention` stripping** — it operates exclusively on pre-cleaned text. All mention stripping is owned by `OnMessageActivityAsync` (Stage 2.2), which is the sole location that calls `Activity.RemoveMentionText` and populates `CommandContext.NormalizedText` before invoking `ICommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync`. The `CommandContext` contains: (a) `NormalizedText` — mention-stripped message text ready for keyword parsing; (b) `TurnContext` — the Bot Framework turn context; (c) `ResolvedIdentity` — the internal user identity from `IIdentityResolver`.
- [ ] Implement unrecognized-input handling: when message text does not match any known command pattern, publish a `MessengerEvent` of subtype `TextEvent` with `EventType = "Text"` and the raw input as payload via `IInboundEventPublisher.PublishAsync` (injected into `CommandDispatcher`) (per `architecture.md` §3.1 `TextEvent` row and `e2e-scenarios.md` lines 43-47), then respond with a help card listing all available commands.

### Dependencies
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-adaptive-card-templates

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Ask command parsing — Given message text `agent ask create e2e test scenarios for update service`, When parsed by `CommandDispatcher`, Then `AskCommandHandler` is invoked with prompt `create e2e test scenarios for update service`.
- [ ] Scenario: Unknown command enqueues TextEvent — Given message text `hello there` that does not match any command pattern, When parsed by `CommandDispatcher`, Then a `MessengerEvent` of subtype `TextEvent` with `EventType = "Text"` is enqueued with the raw input `hello there` as payload, and the dispatcher returns a help card listing all available commands (`agent ask`, `agent status`, `approve`, `reject`, `escalate`, `pause`, `resume`).
- [ ] Scenario: Text approve with explicit questionId — Given a message `approve q-123` is dispatched to `CommandDispatcher`, When `ApproveCommandHandler` processes it, Then it calls `IAgentQuestionStore.GetByIdAsync("q-123")`, validates `approve` is in `AllowedActions`, transitions `Status` from `Open` to `Resolved` via `TryUpdateStatusAsync`, and emits a `HumanDecisionEvent` with `ActionValue = "approve"` and `QuestionId = "q-123"`.
- [ ] Scenario: Text reject with explicit questionId — Given a message `reject q-456` is dispatched to `CommandDispatcher`, When `RejectCommandHandler` processes it, Then it calls `IAgentQuestionStore.GetByIdAsync("q-456")`, validates `reject` is in `AllowedActions`, transitions `Status` from `Open` to `Resolved`, and emits a `HumanDecisionEvent` with `ActionValue = "reject"` and `QuestionId = "q-456"`.
- [ ] Scenario: Bare approve resolves most recent open question — Given conversation `conv-1` has exactly one open `AgentQuestion` with `QuestionId = "q-789"`, When user sends bare `approve` (no questionId argument), Then `ApproveCommandHandler` calls `IAgentQuestionStore.GetOpenByConversationAsync("conv-1")`, receives a single-item list containing `q-789`, and approves it.
- [ ] Scenario: Bare approve with multiple open questions returns disambiguation — Given conversation `conv-1` has two open `AgentQuestion` records (`q-100` and `q-101`), When user sends bare `approve`, Then `ApproveCommandHandler` calls `IAgentQuestionStore.GetOpenByConversationAsync("conv-1")`, receives a two-item list, and returns a disambiguation Adaptive Card listing both questions with their `QuestionId`s, `Title`s, and `CreatedAt` timestamps, and does NOT resolve either.
- [ ] Scenario: @mention stripped before dispatch — Given a channel message with text `<at>AgentBot</at> agent status`, When `OnMessageActivityAsync` (Stage 2.2) strips mentions and passes the cleaned text `agent status` to `CommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync`, Then `StatusCommandHandler` is invoked with no mention artifacts in the command text. Note: `CommandDispatcher` itself does NOT strip mentions — it receives pre-cleaned text from the activity handler.

## Stage 3.3: Card State and Question Persistence

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Implement `SqlCardStateStore : ICardStateStore` — the concrete SQL-backed implementation of the `ICardStateStore` interface (defined in Stage 2.1) that persists the mapping of `QuestionId` → Teams `ActivityId` (message ID), `ConversationId`, and `ConversationReferenceJson` (serialized conversation reference). This store tracks the Teams-specific message identity and conversation rehydration data for card update/delete operations — it does NOT store the full `AgentQuestion` payload or allowed actions (that is `IAgentQuestionStore` below). Backed by a SQL table `CardStates` with columns: `QuestionId` (PK), `ActivityId`, `ConversationId`, `ConversationReferenceJson` (the serialized `ConversationReference` captured at send time — enables background services like `QuestionExpiryProcessor` and `OutboxRetryEngine` to rehydrate the Bot Framework conversation context via `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync` for `UpdateActivityAsync`/`DeleteActivityAsync` without an active turn context), `Status` (Pending/Answered/Expired), `CreatedAt`, `UpdatedAt`. Register `SqlCardStateStore` as `ICardStateStore` in DI, replacing the `NoOpCardStateStore` stub registered in Stage 2.1.
- [ ] Define and implement `SqlAgentQuestionStore : IAgentQuestionStore` — the concrete implementation of the `IAgentQuestionStore` interface (defined in Stage 1.2) that persists the full `AgentQuestion` payload including allowed actions. Backed by a SQL table `AgentQuestions` with columns: `QuestionId` (PK), `AgentId`, `TaskId`, `TenantId`, `TargetUserId`, `TargetChannelId`, `ConversationId` (string — the Teams conversation ID where the question was sent; used by `GetOpenByConversationAsync` and `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` to support bare `approve`/`reject` text commands; populated by `SendQuestionAsync`/`TeamsProactiveNotifier` at card-send time), `Title`, `Body`, `Severity`, `AllowedActionsJson` (serialized JSON of `IReadOnlyList<HumanAction>`), `ExpiresAt`, `CorrelationId`, `Status` (Open/Resolved/Expired), `CreatedAt` (DateTimeOffset — set to `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow` by `SaveAsync`; required for `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` and `GetOpenByConversationAsync` ordering), `ResolvedAt`. The `TenantId` column ensures proactive routing lookups can pass the tenant to `IConversationReferenceStore`. The `AllowedActionsJson` column is deserialized on read so callers receive the typed `AllowedActions` list. Add a filtered index on `(ConversationId, Status) WHERE Status = 'Open'` to support efficient `GetOpenByConversationAsync` and `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` queries. Add a filtered index on `(Status, ExpiresAt) WHERE Status = 'Open'` to support efficient `GetOpenExpiredAsync` scans by `QuestionExpiryProcessor`. Implement `UpdateConversationIdAsync` as a targeted `UPDATE AgentQuestions SET ConversationId = @conversationId WHERE QuestionId = @questionId` SQL statement — this is called by `SendQuestionAsync` (Stage 2.3) and `TeamsProactiveNotifier` (Stage 4.2) after the proactive send completes to populate the conversation ID for bare `approve`/`reject` resolution. Implement `GetOpenByConversationAsync(conversationId)` as `SELECT ... WHERE ConversationId = @conversationId AND Status = 'Open' ORDER BY CreatedAt DESC` — returns ALL open questions for the conversation; used by `ApproveCommandHandler`/`RejectCommandHandler` for single-target-vs-disambiguation branching. Implement `GetOpenExpiredAsync(cutoff, batchSize)` as `SELECT TOP(@batchSize) ... WHERE Status = 'Open' AND ExpiresAt < @cutoff ORDER BY ExpiresAt ASC` — used by `QuestionExpiryProcessor` to discover questions eligible for expiry.
- [ ] Implement `CardActionHandler : ICardActionHandler` class in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Cards` (per `architecture.md` §2.6 lines 139-147). This is the concrete implementation of the `ICardActionHandler` interface (defined in Stage 2.1); it replaces the `NoOpCardActionHandler` stub registered in Stage 2.1 via DI override. Constructor accepts `IAgentQuestionStore`, `ICardStateStore`, `ITeamsCardLifecycleService`, `IInboundEventPublisher`, `IAuditLogger`, and `ILogger<CardActionHandler>`. Core responsibilities: (1) extract `ActionId` and optional comment from `Activity.Value`; (2) resolve the originating `AgentQuestion` via `IAgentQuestionStore.GetByIdAsync(questionId)` to retrieve the full question including `AllowedActions`; (3) validate that the submitted `ActionValue` is in the question's `AllowedActions` list — reject with an error card if not; (4) check `AgentQuestion.Status` and reject if already `Resolved` or `Expired` (first-writer-wins durable idempotency); (5) atomically transition `Status` from `Open` to `Resolved` via `IAgentQuestionStore.TryUpdateStatusAsync(questionId, "Open", "Resolved")` — if this returns `false` (another pod resolved concurrently, per `architecture.md` §6.3 line 957), return a "decision already recorded" response without emitting a `HumanDecisionEvent`. Register `CardActionHandler` as `ICardActionHandler` singleton in DI, replacing the `NoOpCardActionHandler` stub.
- [ ] Add event publication, card lifecycle update, and audit logging to `CardActionHandler`: after a successful status transition, (1) produce a `HumanDecisionEvent` and publish it via `IInboundEventPublisher.PublishAsync` to the inbound event channel; (2) update the original card by calling `ITeamsCardLifecycleService.UpdateCardToResolvedAsync(questionId, actingUserId, actionValue)` — this delegates card rehydration and `UpdateActivityAsync` to the lifecycle service (interface defined in Stage 2.1; concrete `TeamsCardLifecycleService` in this stage below); (3) emit a `CardActionReceived` audit entry via `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` with `EventType = "CardActionReceived"`, `ActorId` set to the acting user's AAD object ID, `TenantId`, `AgentId` from the resolved `AgentQuestion`, `Action` set to the submitted `ActionValue`, `PayloadJson` containing the sanitized card action payload, and `Outcome = "Success"` (or `"Rejected"` if the action was invalid or the question was already resolved). This satisfies `tech-spec.md` §4.3 lines 120 and 127. `OnAdaptiveCardInvokeAsync` in `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` (Stage 2.2) delegates to this handler via the `ICardActionHandler` interface.
- [ ] Implement `TeamsCardLifecycleService : ITeamsCardLifecycleService` class in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Cards` — the concrete implementation of the `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` interface (defined in Stage 2.1). Constructor injects `CloudAdapter`, `ICardStateStore`, `AdaptiveCardBuilder` (Stage 3.1), and `ILogger<TeamsCardLifecycleService>`. `UpdateCardToResolvedAsync` implementation: (1) retrieve `TeamsCardState` via `ICardStateStore.GetByQuestionIdAsync(questionId)` to obtain `ActivityId`, `ConversationId`, and `ConversationReferenceJson`; (2) deserialize `ConversationReferenceJson` into a `ConversationReference`; (3) call `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync` with the deserialized reference to create a proactive turn; (4) inside the callback, build a resolved-status replacement card via `AdaptiveCardBuilder.RenderResolvedCard(questionId, resolvedByUserId, actionValue)` and call `turnContext.UpdateActivityAsync(activityId)` to replace the original approval card; (5) update card state status to `Answered` via `ICardStateStore.UpdateStatusAsync`. `DeleteCardAsync` implementation: same rehydration pattern — (1) retrieve `TeamsCardState`, (2) deserialize reference, (3) `ContinueConversationAsync`, (4) `turnContext.DeleteActivityAsync(activityId)`, (5) update card state to `Expired`. This service is the SOLE code path for card update/delete — `CardActionHandler` calls `UpdateCardToResolvedAsync`; `QuestionExpiryProcessor` calls `DeleteCardAsync`; neither calls `UpdateActivityAsync`/`DeleteActivityAsync` directly. Register `TeamsCardLifecycleService` as `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` singleton in DI, replacing the `NoOpCardLifecycleService` stub registered in Stage 2.1.
- [ ] Implement `QuestionExpiryProcessor` as a `BackgroundService` that periodically scans for expired questions using `IAgentQuestionStore.GetOpenExpiredAsync(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow, batchSize, ct)` (method defined in Stage 1.2's `IAgentQuestionStore` contract). The processor injects `IAgentQuestionStore`, `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` (interface defined in Stage 2.1; concrete `TeamsCardLifecycleService` implemented above in this stage), and `TeamsMessagingOptions`. For each expired question returned by `GetOpenExpiredAsync`: (1) atomically transition `Status` from `Open` to `Expired` via `IAgentQuestionStore.TryUpdateStatusAsync(questionId, "Open", "Expired")` — if this returns `false`, another process already resolved or expired the question; skip it; (2) call `ITeamsCardLifecycleService.DeleteCardAsync(questionId)` to delete the expired card from the Teams conversation (the lifecycle service handles `TeamsCardState` lookup, `ConversationReference` rehydration, and `DeleteActivityAsync` — the processor does NOT call `CloudAdapter` or `ICardStateStore` directly). The processor runs on a configurable interval (default: 60 seconds) and processes expired questions in batches (default batch size: 50, configurable via `TeamsMessagingOptions`). Register `QuestionExpiryProcessor` as a hosted service in DI.
- [ ] Add `ActivityId` and `ConversationReferenceJson` capture for proactively sent Adaptive Cards: in `SendQuestionAsync` (in `TeamsMessengerConnector`), after sending via `ContinueConversationAsync`, read the `ResourceResponse.Id` returned by `SendActivityAsync` and serialize the active `ConversationReference` (obtained from the proactive turn context via `Activity.GetConversationReference()`). Persist both to `ICardStateStore.SaveAsync` as a `TeamsCardState` with `ActivityId`, `ConversationId`, and `ConversationReferenceJson` populated, so that proactive approval cards can be updated or deleted later by `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` and background services using the stored reference. Also call `IAgentQuestionStore.UpdateConversationIdAsync(question.QuestionId, conversationId, ct)` to populate the `AgentQuestion.ConversationId` with the Teams conversation ID from the proactive turn context, enabling `GetMostRecentOpenByConversationAsync` queries for bare `approve`/`reject` commands. Note: `ActivityId` and `ConversationReferenceJson` capture for proactive sends via `ProactiveNotifier` is deferred to Stage 4.2 where `ProactiveNotifier` is created — that stage includes a dedicated step for capture in proactive delivery.

### Dependencies
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-command-dispatcher

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Card update after approval — Given an approval card was sent with `ActivityId = "act-1"`, When the user approves, Then the card is updated to show "Approved by {user}" via `UpdateActivityAsync`.
- [ ] Scenario: Card delete on expiry — Given a question with `QuestionId = "q-exp"`, `Status = "Open"`, and `ExpiresAt` 5 minutes in the past, and a card with `ActivityId = "act-exp"` stored in `ICardStateStore`, When `QuestionExpiryProcessor` runs its periodic scan, Then it transitions the question's `Status` from `Open` to `Expired` via `TryUpdateStatusAsync`, deletes the card via `DeleteActivityAsync` using `ActivityId = "act-exp"`, and updates the card state status to `Expired`.
- [ ] Scenario: State store persistence — Given a card is sent and its `ActivityId` is stored, When the service restarts and the store is queried, Then the `ActivityId` is still retrievable.
- [ ] Scenario: AgentQuestion round-trip via IAgentQuestionStore — Given an `AgentQuestion` with `QuestionId = "q-42"`, `AllowedActions = [Approve, Reject]`, `TargetUserId = "user-1"`, and `TargetChannelId = null` is saved via `IAgentQuestionStore.SaveAsync`, When retrieved via `GetByIdAsync("q-42")`, Then the returned `AgentQuestion` has all fields including deserialized `AllowedActions` matching the original, and `TargetUserId = "user-1"` and `TargetChannelId = null`.
- [ ] Scenario: Allowed action validation via stored question — Given an `AgentQuestion` with `AllowedActions = [Approve, Reject]` is persisted in `IAgentQuestionStore`, When a card action submission with `ActionValue = "escalate"` (not in `AllowedActions`) is processed, Then `CardActionHandler` rejects the action because `"escalate"` is not in the stored question's `AllowedActions` list.
- [ ] Scenario: First-writer-wins concurrent resolution — Given an `AgentQuestion` with `QuestionId = "q-99"` and `Status = "Open"`, When two pods concurrently call `IAgentQuestionStore.TryUpdateStatusAsync("q-99", "Open", "Resolved")`, Then exactly one call returns `true` (succeeds) and the other returns `false` (rejected), ensuring only one `HumanDecisionEvent` is emitted (per `architecture.md` §6.3 lines 955-957).
- [ ] Scenario: Multi-approver release gate uses separate questions — Given a release gate requiring 2 approvers (Alice and Bob), When the orchestrator creates two separate `AgentQuestion` records (`Q-gate-a` for Alice, `Q-gate-b` for Bob) each with `Status = Open`, And Alice approves her card (transitioning `Q-gate-a` from `Open` → `Resolved` via `TryUpdateStatusAsync`), And Bob approves his card (transitioning `Q-gate-b` from `Open` → `Resolved` independently), Then each approval is processed by `CardActionHandler` as a standard single-decision first-writer-wins lifecycle, and the orchestrator's workflow layer aggregates the two `HumanDecisionEvent` records to meet the approval threshold (per `architecture.md` §6.3.1 lines 965-978 and `e2e-scenarios.md` lines 773-791).
- [ ] Scenario: CardActionReceived audit entry emitted — Given a user submits an Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` with `actionValue = "approve"` and `questionId = "q-audit-1"`, When `CardActionHandler` processes the action successfully, Then `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` is called (verified against mock) with `EventType = "CardActionReceived"`, `ActorId` set to the user's AAD object ID, `TenantId` matching the user's tenant, `AgentId` matching the question's `AgentId`, `Action = "approve"`, and `Outcome = "Success"`. This satisfies `tech-spec.md` §4.3 line 120 requiring every Adaptive Card action callback to produce an append-only audit record with `CardActionReceived` event type (per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 line 127).
- [ ] Scenario: CardActionReceived audit on rejected action — Given a user submits a card action with `actionValue = "escalate"` for question `q-audit-2` whose `AllowedActions` only includes `[Approve, Reject]`, When `CardActionHandler` rejects the invalid action, Then `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` is called with `EventType = "CardActionReceived"`, `Action = "escalate"`, and `Outcome = "Rejected"`.

## Stage 3.4: Message Extension Handler

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `MessageExtensionHandler` class in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Extensions` that handles Teams message-extension action commands (`composeExtension/submitAction`). When a user invokes a message action (e.g., right-clicks a message and selects "Forward to Agent"), the handler extracts the source message content from the invoke payload.
- [ ] Override `OnTeamsMessagingExtensionSubmitActionAsync` in `TeamsSwarmActivityHandler` to delegate to `MessageExtensionHandler`, passing the `MessagingExtensionAction` data.
- [ ] Implement message content extraction: parse the `MessagingExtensionAction.MessagePayload` to retrieve the forwarded message text, sender, and timestamp.
- [ ] Delegate extracted message-action text to `ICommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync` (interface defined in Stage 1.2; concrete `CommandDispatcher` implementation in Stage 3.2; per `architecture.md` §2.5 cross-doc note line 125 which says implementation call sites use `ICommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync`) to parse the forwarded message as an agent command and publish a `MessengerEvent` of subtype `CommandEvent` with `EventType = "AgentTaskRequest"` and `Source = "MessageAction"` to the inbound buffer (aligned with `architecture.md` §2.15 and `e2e-scenarios.md` §Message Actions). The `Source = "MessageAction"` field on the domain `MessengerEvent` distinguishes message-extension submissions from direct text commands for downstream processing.
- [ ] After extracting and dispatching the message-action payload, log an audit entry with `EventType = "MessageActionReceived"` via `IAuditLogger.LogAsync`, recording the acting user's AAD object ID, tenant ID, the source message text, and the resulting correlation/task ID. Message actions log as `MessageActionReceived` — a dedicated audit event type distinct from `CommandReceived` — because message-action submissions arrive through the `composeExtension/submitAction` invoke mechanism rather than direct text commands, and distinguishing them in the audit trail supports compliance filtering and forensic analysis (per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 Canonical Audit Record Schema, which defines exactly seven canonical `EventType` values including `MessageActionReceived`).
- [ ] Return a task-submitted confirmation card to the user via `MessagingExtensionActionResponse` containing a success message and the created task/correlation ID.
- [ ] Update the Teams app manifest `composeExtensions` entry to set `fetchTask: false` (direct submit) and configure the `commands` array with the action command definition including `id`, `title`, `description`, and `type: "action"`.

### Dependencies
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-command-dispatcher

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Message action forwarding — Given a user right-clicks a message and selects "Forward to Agent", When the message extension submit action is received, Then `MessageExtensionHandler` extracts the message text and dispatches via `ICommandDispatcher.DispatchAsync`, publishing a `CommandEvent` with `EventType = "AgentTaskRequest"` and `Source = "MessageAction"`.
- [ ] Scenario: Confirmation card returned — Given a successful message-extension submit, When `OnTeamsMessagingExtensionSubmitActionAsync` completes, Then a `MessagingExtensionActionResponse` with a confirmation Adaptive Card is returned to the user.
- [ ] Scenario: Empty message payload — Given a message action invoke with no message payload (e.g., triggered from command box), When `MessageExtensionHandler` processes it, Then a descriptive error card is returned asking the user to select a message first.
- [ ] Scenario: Message action audit call — Given a user submits a message action forwarding a message to an agent, When `MessageExtensionHandler` completes dispatch, Then `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` is called (verified against mock) with `EventType = "MessageActionReceived"` (message actions log as `MessageActionReceived` per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 Canonical Audit Record Schema — seven canonical values; `MessageActionReceived` is a dedicated audit event type for message-extension submissions), `ActorId` set to the user's AAD object ID, `TenantId` matching the user's tenant, `Action` set to `"message_action_forward"`, and `PayloadJson` containing the forwarded message text. Note: this test uses a mock `IAuditLogger` because `SqlAuditLogger` is not implemented until Stage 5.2; end-to-end audit persistence is validated in Phase 7.

# Phase 4: Proactive Messaging and Conversation Reference Management

## Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core

## Stage 4.1: Conversation Reference Store Implementation

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Implement `SqlConversationReferenceStore : IConversationReferenceStore` using Entity Framework Core with a `ConversationReferences` table containing: `Id` (PK), `AadObjectId` (string, nullable — Entra AAD object ID captured from `Activity.From.AadObjectId` at install time and refreshed on message receipt; null for channel-scoped references), `InternalUserId` (string, nullable — internal user ID mapped by `IIdentityResolver`; populated when identity resolution first succeeds for this AAD object ID; null until the user's first authorized interaction; the orchestrator uses this value when setting `AgentQuestion.TargetUserId` for proactive delivery), `TenantId`, `ChannelId` (nullable — null for personal-chat references), `ServiceUrl`, `ConversationJson` (serialized `ConversationReference`), `IsActive` (bool, default `true` — set to `false` by `MarkInactiveAsync` on uninstall), `DeactivatedAt` (DateTimeOffset, nullable — timestamp when marked inactive), `DeactivationReason` (string, nullable — `Uninstalled` or `StaleReference`), `CreatedAt`, `UpdatedAt`. The dual-key model (per `architecture.md` §TeamsConversationReference lines 383-384) supports two lookup paths: Teams-side operations use `AadObjectId` (captured from `Activity.From.AadObjectId`); orchestrator-side proactive delivery uses `InternalUserId` (populated by `IIdentityResolver`). The table supports two types of references: user-scoped (personal chat, keyed by `AadObjectId + TenantId`) and channel-scoped (team channel, keyed by `ChannelId + TenantId`).
- [ ] Create EF Core migration for the `ConversationReferences` table with: a unique filtered index on `(AadObjectId, TenantId) WHERE AadObjectId IS NOT NULL` for user-scoped references (Teams-side lookup key), a non-unique filtered index on `(InternalUserId, TenantId) WHERE InternalUserId IS NOT NULL` for proactive routing lookups (orchestrator-side key), a unique filtered index on `(ChannelId, TenantId) WHERE ChannelId IS NOT NULL` for channel-scoped references, a non-clustered index on `TenantId`, and a filtered index on `IsActive = true` for efficient active-reference queries used by `GetAllActiveAsync` and proactive send pre-checks.
- [ ] Implement `MarkInactiveAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)` to set `IsActive = false`, `DeactivatedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow`, and `DeactivationReason = "Uninstalled"` without deleting the row (retained for audit). Keyed by `(AadObjectId, TenantId)` since uninstall events provide the AAD object ID from `Activity.From.AadObjectId`.
- [ ] Implement `MarkInactiveByChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)` to set `IsActive = false`, `DeactivatedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow`, and `DeactivationReason = "Uninstalled"` on the channel-scoped conversation reference keyed by `(ChannelId, TenantId)`. Called by `OnTeamsMembersRemovedAsync` (Stage 2.2) when a bot is removed from a team — each channel reference in the team is marked inactive for audit retention (per `architecture.md` §4.2 lines 543-544).
- [ ] Implement `DeleteByChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)` for administrative cleanup: permanently removes channel-scoped references after the enterprise audit retention period has elapsed. This method is NOT called by the automated uninstall flow — it is invoked only by an operator-initiated maintenance task (per `architecture.md` §4.2 line 545).
- [ ] Implement `IsActiveAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)` to check `IsActive` status before proactive sends, used by `InstallationStateGate` (Stage 5.1) and `ProactiveNotifier` (Stage 4.2) to skip inactive references.
- [ ] Implement `GetByAadObjectIdAsync(string tenantId, string aadObjectId)` and `GetByInternalUserIdAsync(string tenantId, string internalUserId)` query methods returning only active references for targeted proactive messaging. `GetByAadObjectIdAsync` is used by Teams-side operations (install, message receipt) to find/update references by the Teams-native AAD identity key. `GetByInternalUserIdAsync` is used by the orchestrator for proactive routing when `AgentQuestion.TargetUserId` is set. Also implement `GetByChannelIdAsync(string tenantId, string channelId)` for channel-scoped lookups.
- [ ] Implement `SaveOrUpdateAsync` with upsert logic supporting both reference types: for user-scoped references, upsert on `(AadObjectId, TenantId)` — if a reference arrives for the same AAD object ID/tenant, update in place and reset `IsActive = true`, `DeactivatedAt = null` (handles re-installation after uninstall); additionally, if `IIdentityResolver` has resolved the user, populate `InternalUserId` on the reference to enable proactive routing by internal ID; for channel-scoped references, upsert on `(ChannelId, TenantId)` — if a reference arrives for the same channel/tenant, update in place similarly. The method inspects whether `AadObjectId` or `ChannelId` is populated to determine the upsert key.

### Dependencies
- _none — start stage_

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Save and retrieve by AAD object ID — Given a conversation reference for AAD object ID `aad-user-1` in tenant `tenant-1`, When saved and then retrieved via `GetByAadObjectIdAsync("tenant-1", "aad-user-1")`, Then the deserialized `ConversationReference` matches the original.
- [ ] Scenario: Retrieve by internal user ID — Given a conversation reference for AAD object ID `aad-user-1` in tenant `tenant-1` with `InternalUserId = "internal-1"` populated after identity resolution, When retrieved via `GetByInternalUserIdAsync("tenant-1", "internal-1")`, Then the reference matches and contains both `AadObjectId = "aad-user-1"` and `InternalUserId = "internal-1"`.
- [ ] Scenario: Upsert on duplicate — Given a reference already exists for `aad-user-1`, When a new reference is saved for the same AAD object ID, Then only one record exists with the updated `ServiceUrl`.
- [ ] Scenario: Multi-tenant isolation — Given references for `tenant-1` and `tenant-2`, When queried for `tenant-1`, Then only `tenant-1` references are returned.
- [ ] Scenario: Channel reference upsert — Given a channel-scoped reference for `channel-general` in `tenant-1` (with null `AadObjectId`), When a new reference arrives for the same `(ChannelId, TenantId)`, Then only one record exists with the updated `ServiceUrl` and the upsert key is `(ChannelId, TenantId)`.
- [ ] Scenario: User and channel references coexist — Given a user-scoped reference for AAD object ID `aad-user-1` in `tenant-1` and a channel-scoped reference for `channel-general` in `tenant-1`, When both are saved, Then two distinct records exist and each can be retrieved independently via `GetByAadObjectIdAsync` and `GetByChannelIdAsync` respectively.
- [ ] Scenario: Channel reference marked inactive on team uninstall — Given an active channel-scoped reference for `channel-general` in `tenant-1`, When `MarkInactiveByChannelAsync("tenant-1", "channel-general")` is called, Then the reference has `IsActive = false`, `DeactivatedAt` is set, and `DeactivationReason = "Uninstalled"`, and the reference is still retrievable for audit (not deleted).
- [ ] Scenario: Channel reference admin delete — Given an inactive channel-scoped reference for `channel-general` in `tenant-1` past the audit retention period, When `DeleteByChannelAsync("tenant-1", "channel-general")` is called, Then the reference is permanently removed from the store.

## Stage 4.2: Proactive Notification Service

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `IProactiveNotifier` interface with methods: `SendProactiveAsync(string tenantId, string userId, MessengerMessage message, CancellationToken ct)`, `SendProactiveQuestionAsync(string tenantId, string userId, AgentQuestion question, CancellationToken ct)`, `SendToChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId, MessengerMessage message, CancellationToken ct)`, and `SendQuestionToChannelAsync(string tenantId, string channelId, AgentQuestion question, CancellationToken ct)`. All methods require `tenantId` as the first parameter because `IConversationReferenceStore` lookups are keyed by `(InternalUserId, TenantId)` for user-targeted sends and `(ChannelId, TenantId)` for channel-targeted sends. For user-targeted methods, the `tenantId` is sourced from `AgentQuestion.TenantId` (populated by the orchestrator); for channel-targeted methods, it is passed directly by the caller.
- [ ] Implement `TeamsProactiveNotifier : IProactiveNotifier` using `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync` with stored conversation references. Inject `AdaptiveCardBuilder` (Stage 3.1) as a constructor dependency — `SendProactiveQuestionAsync` and `SendQuestionToChannelAsync` use `AdaptiveCardBuilder.RenderQuestion(agentQuestion)` to render `AgentQuestion` records as Adaptive Cards before sending. For user-targeted sends, use the `tenantId` parameter and look up by `(InternalUserId, TenantId)` via `IConversationReferenceStore.GetByInternalUserIdAsync(tenantId, userId)` (the `InternalUserId` on the stored reference was populated when `IIdentityResolver` first mapped the user's `AadObjectId` — per `architecture.md` §TeamsConversationReference line 384); for channel-targeted sends, look up by `(ChannelId, TenantId)` via `GetByChannelIdAsync(tenantId, channelId)`.
- [ ] Implement conversation reference rehydration: deserialize stored `ConversationReference` JSON and invoke `ContinueConversationAsync` with the app credentials.
- [ ] Add proactive message delivery via direct `ContinueConversationAsync` calls as an interim implementation; this will be replaced by outbox-mediated sends in Phase 6 Stage 6.1 (the direct-send code path is removed when Stage 6.1's outbox wiring step lands).
- [ ] Implement notification routing: determine whether to send to personal chat or team channel based on which field is populated on `AgentQuestion` — if `TargetUserId` is non-null, route to personal chat via `SendProactiveQuestionAsync(question.TenantId, question.TargetUserId, question)`; if `TargetChannelId` is non-null, route to team channel via `SendQuestionToChannelAsync(question.TenantId, question.TargetChannelId, question)`. Exactly one of `TargetUserId` or `TargetChannelId` must be non-null (validated on `AgentQuestion` construction).
- [ ] Add `ActivityId` and `ConversationReferenceJson` capture in `TeamsProactiveNotifier` for proactively sent Adaptive Cards: after sending a card via `ContinueConversationAsync`, read the `ResourceResponse.Id` returned by the send call, and serialize the `ConversationReference` from the active proactive turn context via `Activity.GetConversationReference()`. Persist both to `ICardStateStore.SaveAsync` as a `TeamsCardState` with `ActivityId`, `ConversationId`, and `ConversationReferenceJson` populated, keyed by `QuestionId`. Also call `IAgentQuestionStore.UpdateConversationIdAsync(question.QuestionId, conversationId, ct)` to populate the `AgentQuestion.ConversationId` with the Teams conversation ID from the proactive turn context (same two-step save pattern as `SendQuestionAsync` in Stage 2.3). This enables Stage 3.3's `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` card update/delete logic and Stage 6.1's outbox retry to locate and modify proactively sent cards using the stored reference without requiring a live turn context. `ICardStateStore` and `IAgentQuestionStore` are injected into `TeamsProactiveNotifier` as constructor dependencies alongside `CloudAdapter` and `IConversationReferenceStore`.

### Dependencies
- phase-proactive-messaging-and-conversation-reference-management/stage-conversation-reference-store-implementation
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-adaptive-card-templates
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-card-state-and-question-persistence

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Proactive question delivery — Given a stored conversation reference for `user-1`, When `SendProactiveQuestionAsync` is called with an `AgentQuestion`, Then an Adaptive Card is delivered to the user's personal chat using `AdaptiveCardBuilder` to render the card.
- [ ] Scenario: Reference not found — Given no conversation reference exists for `user-2`, When `SendProactiveQuestionAsync` is called, Then a `ConversationReferenceNotFoundException` is thrownand the caller logs the failure for later outbox-based retry (available in Phase 6).
- [ ] Scenario: Direct delivery latency (INTERIM — replaced by outbox-mediated path in Stage 6.1) — Given a stored conversation reference and a rendered Adaptive Card, When `SendProactiveQuestionAsync` delivers the card directly via `ContinueConversationAsync` (interim direct-send path before Stage 6.1 outbox wiring), Then delivery completes within P95 < 3 seconds. Note: this is an interim-only scenario validating the direct delivery path that exists between Stage 4.2 and Stage 6.1. Once Stage 6.1 wires all sends through the outbox, this direct-send code path is removed and this scenario is superseded by Stage 6.3's `Delivery histogram` test which measures the canonical P95 SLA (< 3 seconds from outbox queue pickup to Bot Connector acknowledgement, per `tech-spec.md` §4.4).
- [ ] Scenario: Channel proactive delivery — Given a stored channel-scoped conversation reference for `channel-general` in `tenant-1`, When `SendToChannelAsync("tenant-1", "channel-general", message)` is called, Then the message is delivered to the team channel (not a personal chat) using the channel's stored `ConversationReference` via `ContinueConversationAsync`.
- [ ] Scenario: Channel question delivery — Given a stored channel reference, When `SendQuestionToChannelAsync` is called with an `AgentQuestion`, Then an Adaptive Card is delivered to the team channel using `AdaptiveCardBuilder` to render the card.

# Phase 5: Security, Identity, and Compliance

## Dependencies
- phase-teams-bot-framework-core

## Stage 5.1: Tenant and Identity Validation

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Enhance `TenantValidationMiddleware` (ASP.NET Core HTTP middleware created in Stage 2.1) with compliance-grade audit logging: replace the basic `ILogger` structured warning (added in Stage 2.1) with a formal `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` call that emits a `SecurityRejection` audit entry with `Outcome = "Rejected"` and `Action = "UnauthorizedTenantRejected"` for each blocked tenant. This is a replacement, not an addition — only ONE audit/log record is emitted per blocked request (the `ILogger` warning from Stage 2.1 is removed and superseded by the `IAuditLogger` call). The middleware continues to set HTTP 403 directly on the ASP.NET Core response (it runs in the HTTP pipeline before `CloudAdapter`, so it has direct control over the HTTP status code) with **no bot response and no Adaptive Card** (per `tech-spec.md` §4.2: tenant allow-list failures are rejected at the HTTP middleware layer before the request reaches `CloudAdapter`, so there is no conversation context in which to send a card — the rejection behavior is unchanged from Stage 2.1).
- [ ] Implement `RbacAuthorizationService : IUserAuthorizationService` (concrete implementation of the interface defined in Stage 1.2) in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Security` with full role-scoped RBAC logic that checks permissions based on `RbacOptions` configuration. Register this implementation in DI to replace the `DefaultDenyAuthorizationService` stub registered in Stage 2.1.
- [ ] Implement `EntraIdentityResolver : IIdentityResolver` (concrete implementation of the interface defined in Stage 1.2) in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Security` that maps the Teams `Activity.From.AadObjectId` (Entra AAD object ID) to an internal user identity record; reject unmapped users with HTTP 200 + Adaptive Card explaining access denial and how to request access (per the two-tier rejection model in `tech-spec.md` §4.2). Register this implementation in DI to replace the `DefaultDenyIdentityResolver` stub registered in Stage 2.1.
- [ ] Create `RbacOptions` configuration class mapping Teams user roles to allowed commands (e.g., `Operator` → all commands, `Approver` → `approve`/`reject`/`agent status`, `Viewer` → `agent status` only).
- [ ] Integrate Entra ID token validation by configuring `BotFrameworkAuthentication` with `AllowedCallers` and tenant restrictions.
- [ ] Implement `InstallationStateGate` that enforces Teams app installation as a prerequisite for proactive messaging: track installation state via `InstallationUpdate` activities (handled by `OnInstallationUpdateActivityAsync` in Stage 2.2); when an uninstall event is received, mark the `ConversationReference` as inactive via `IConversationReferenceStore.MarkInactiveAsync` (concrete implementation from Stage 4.1, available via this stage's dependency on `stage-conversation-reference-store-implementation`); before any proactive send, verify the target reference is active via `IConversationReferenceStore.IsActiveAsync` — if inactive (uninstalled), skip the Bot Framework call, dead-letter the message via `IMessageOutbox.DeadLetterAsync` (interface from Stage 1.2; concrete `SqlMessageOutbox` implementation is wired in Stage 6.1 — `InstallationStateGate` is unit-tested with a mock `IMessageOutbox`, integration-tested in Phase 7 after Stage 6.1 lands), and log an audit entry with `EventType = "Error"` and `Outcome = "Failed"`. Stale references (valid installation but reference became invalid, e.g., user removed from tenant) are detected reactively via 403/404 on send attempt (per `tech-spec.md` §4.2 R-2).
- [ ] Add rejection response: unauthorized users receive a polite card explaining they lack access and how to request it.
- [ ] Create `TeamsAppPolicyOptions` configuration class in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Security` with properties: `RequireAdminConsent` (bool, default `true`), `AllowedAppCatalogScopes` (list of `"organization"` | `"personal"`), and `BlockSideloading` (bool, default `true` in production). Bind from configuration in `Program.cs` and validate at startup that `MicrosoftAppId` has a corresponding Entra ID app registration with the `TeamsAppInstallation.ReadForUser.All` Graph API permission (required for reading installation state).
- [ ] Implement `TeamsAppPolicyHealthCheck : IHealthCheck` in `AgentSwarm.Messaging.Teams.Security` that calls the Microsoft Graph `/appCatalogs/teamsApps?$filter=externalId eq '{MicrosoftAppId}'` endpoint to verify the bot is published to the organization catalog (when `AllowedAppCatalogScopes` includes `"organization"`). Returns `Healthy` when the app is found; returns `Degraded` with detail explaining the app is not found and admins must publish it via Teams admin center when the app is missing. Logs a warning if the app is not found. Register as a health check in `Program.cs`.
- [ ] Create `docs/stories/qq-MICROSOFT-TEAMS-MESS/deployment-checklist.md` documenting the Entra ID admin consent steps: (1) register the bot app in Entra ID with `TeamsAppInstallation.ReadForUser.All` and `User.Read` delegated permissions, (2) grant admin consent in the Azure portal, (3) configure Teams admin center app setup policy to pre-install or allow the bot for target users/groups, (4) set `RequireAdminConsent = true` in `TeamsAppPolicyOptions` to enforce that only admin-consented installations are trusted. This satisfies the story requirement "Integrate with Entra ID / Teams app installation policies" by providing operator documentation for admin deployment policy configuration.

### Dependencies
- phase-proactive-messaging-and-conversation-reference-management/stage-conversation-reference-store-implementation
- phase-proactive-messaging-and-conversation-reference-management/stage-proactive-notification-service

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Unauthorized tenant rejected — Given `AllowedTenantIds` contains `tenant-A`, When an HTTP POST arrives at `/api/messages` from `tenant-B`, Then the ASP.NET Core `TenantValidationMiddleware` short-circuits the HTTP pipeline before `CloudAdapter` processes the request, returns HTTP 403 Forbidden, and sends no reply activity, preventing the activity handler from processing the request.
- [ ] Scenario: RBAC enforcement — Given user `viewer-1` has role `Viewer`, When they send `approve`, Then a rejection message is returned explaining insufficient permissions.
- [ ] Scenario: Authorized user succeeds — Given user `ops-1` has role `Operator`, When they send `agent ask plan migration`, Then the command is dispatched successfully.
- [ ] Scenario: Security rejection audit uses Outcome Rejected — Given user `eve@external.com` is not identity-mapped (unmapped user), When `eve` sends any command and `IIdentityResolver.ResolveAsync` rejects her, Then `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` is called (verified against mock) with `EventType = "SecurityRejection"`, `Outcome = "Rejected"`, `Action = "UnmappedUserRejected"`, `ActorId` set to `eve`'s AAD object ID, and `TenantId` matching her tenant. Rejection reason codes (`UnmappedUserRejected`, `UnauthorizedTenantRejected`, `InsufficientRoleRejected`) appear in `Action`, NOT in `Outcome` — `Outcome` uses only the four canonical values (`Success`, `Rejected`, `Failed`, `DeadLettered`) per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 and `architecture.md` §3.2. Note: this test uses a mock `IAuditLogger` because `SqlAuditLogger` is not implemented until Stage 5.2 (which depends on this stage); end-to-end audit persistence is validated in Phase 7.
- [ ] Scenario: Admin deployment policy health check — Given `TeamsAppPolicyOptions.AllowedAppCatalogScopes` includes `"organization"` and the bot's `MicrosoftAppId` is published to the organization app catalog, When `TeamsAppPolicyHealthCheck` runs, Then it returns `Healthy`. Given the bot is NOT published to the catalog, When the health check runs, Then it returns `Degraded` with detail explaining the app is not found in the organization catalog and admins must publish it via Teams admin center.

## Stage 5.2: Audit Logging Implementation

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Implement `SqlAuditLogger : IAuditLogger` writing to an append-only `AuditLog` table with columns matching the canonical schema from `tech-spec.md` §4.3 (Canonical Audit Record Schema): `Id` (surrogate PK), `Timestamp` (DateTimeOffset), `CorrelationId` (string), `EventType` (string — exactly seven canonical values: `CommandReceived`, `MessageSent`, `CardActionReceived`, `SecurityRejection`, `ProactiveNotification`, `MessageActionReceived`, `Error`; message actions (Teams message-extension submissions) log as `MessageActionReceived` — a dedicated audit event type distinct from `CommandReceived` — because message-action submissions arrive through the `composeExtension/submitAction` invoke mechanism rather than direct text commands, and distinguishing them in the audit trail supports compliance filtering and forensic analysis; the `Source` field on the domain `MessengerEvent` additionally marks the origination for downstream processing, per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 Canonical Audit Record Schema), `ActorId` (string — AAD object ID or agent ID), `ActorType` (string — `User` or `Agent`), `TenantId` (string), `AgentId` (string, nullable — the agent whose task or question triggered this event; present on all events tied to an agent task including human-originated actions; null for events not associated with a specific agent; per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 lines 139 and 146), `TaskId` (string, nullable), `ConversationId` (string, nullable), `Action` (string), `PayloadJson` (string — sanitized JSON), `Outcome` (string — `Success`, `Rejected`, `Failed`, `DeadLettered`), `Checksum` (SHA-256 of row content for tamper detection).
- [ ] Create EF Core migration for the `AuditLog` table with a clustered index on `Timestamp` and non-clustered index on `CorrelationId`. Apply database-level immutability enforcement: create an `INSTEAD OF UPDATE` trigger on the `AuditLog` table that raises an error (`RAISERROR` / `THROW`) and rolls back the update — this prevents direct database mutations (not just application-level restrictions). Also create an `INSTEAD OF DELETE` trigger that similarly blocks row deletions. Grant the application's database user only `INSERT` and `SELECT` permissions on the `AuditLog` table (no `UPDATE` or `DELETE` grants) as a defense-in-depth measure alongside the triggers. The combination of DB triggers (preventing mutation even by privileged queries) and restrictive grants (preventing mutation by the application service principal) provides a verifiable immutability guarantee suitable for enterprise compliance audit.
- [ ] Instrument all command handlers to emit audit entries: log the command, user identity, tenant, timestamp, and outcome.
- [ ] Instrument proactive message sends to emit audit entries: log the target user, message type, correlation ID, and delivery status.
- [ ] Verify that `CardActionHandler` (Stage 3.3) already emits `CardActionReceived` audit entries via its injected `IAuditLogger` dependency (responsibility #8 in its implementation step). With `SqlAuditLogger` now registered in DI (replacing `NoOpAuditLogger`), all card action audit entries are persisted to the `AuditLog` table. No additional instrumentation is needed in this stage — the audit call site exists in Stage 3.3's `CardActionHandler`. This step validates audit coverage completeness: every inbound command (`CommandReceived`), every outbound notification (`ProactiveNotification`), and every Adaptive Card action callback (`CardActionReceived`) now produces an append-only audit record per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 line 120.
- [ ] Implement `AuditLogQueryService` with methods for compliance review: `GetByDateRangeAsync`, `GetByActorAsync`, `GetByCorrelationIdAsync`.

### Dependencies
- phase-security-identity-and-compliance/stage-tenant-and-identity-validation
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing/stage-card-state-and-question-persistence

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Command audit trail— Given user `ops-1` sends the text command `agent ask plan migration`, When the command completes, Then an `AuditLog` entry exists with `EventType = "CommandReceived"`, `ActorId = "ops-1"` (AAD object ID), `ActorType = "User"`, `TenantId` matching the user's tenant, `Action = "agent ask"`, `TaskId` referencing the associated task, `ConversationId` matching the Teams conversation, `PayloadJson` containing sanitized command details, and `Outcome = "Success"`. Text commands use `EventType = "CommandReceived"` (per `e2e-scenarios.md` line 550); Adaptive Card action callbacks use `EventType = "CardActionReceived"` (per `e2e-scenarios.md` line 579).
- [ ] Scenario: Immutability enforced at database level — Given an audit entry with `Id = 1` is written to the `AuditLog` table, When a raw SQL `UPDATE AuditLog SET Action = 'tampered' WHERE Id = 1` is executed directly against the database (bypassing the application), Then the `INSTEAD OF UPDATE` trigger fires, raises an error, and the row remains unchanged. Similarly, when a raw SQL `DELETE FROM AuditLog WHERE Id = 1` is executed, the `INSTEAD OF DELETE` trigger fires and the row is retained.
- [ ] Scenario: Checksum integrity — Given an audit entry with known content, When the checksum is recomputed from the stored fields, Then it matches the stored `Checksum` value.
- [ ] Scenario: CardActionReceived audit persisted — Given `SqlAuditLogger` is registered in DI (replacing `NoOpAuditLogger`) and a user submits an Adaptive Card `Action.Submit` with `actionValue = "approve"` for question `q-aud-persist`, When `CardActionHandler` processes the action and calls `IAuditLogger.LogAsync` with `EventType = "CardActionReceived"`, Then an `AuditLog` row exists in the database with `EventType = "CardActionReceived"`, `ActorId` matching the user's AAD object ID, `AgentId` from the question, `Action = "approve"`, `Outcome = "Success"`, and a valid `Checksum`. This validates end-to-end audit persistence for Adaptive Card action callbacks per `tech-spec.md` §4.3 line 120.

# Phase 6: Reliability and Performance

## Dependencies
- phase-adaptive-cards-and-command-processing
- phase-proactive-messaging-and-conversation-reference-management

## Stage 6.1: Outbox Pattern and Retry Engine

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Implement `SqlMessageOutbox : IMessageOutbox` with an `OutboxMessages` table containing: `Id`, `Payload` (JSON), `DestinationType` (personal/channel/CardUpdate/CardDelete — `CardUpdate` and `CardDelete` types are used for Adaptive Card update/delete retry operations wired later in this stage), `DestinationId`, `ActivityId` (nullable — populated for `CardUpdate`/`CardDelete` entries to identify the target card), `ConversationId` (nullable — populated for `CardUpdate`/`CardDelete` entries), `ConversationReferenceJson` (nullable — serialized `ConversationReference` required for all outbox entries; for send operations, the reference is resolved from `IConversationReferenceStore` at enqueue time; for `CardUpdate`/`CardDelete` entries, the reference is copied from `TeamsCardState.ConversationReferenceJson` via `ICardStateStore.GetByQuestionIdAsync`; `OutboxRetryEngine` deserializes this field to rehydrate the Bot Framework conversation context via `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync` before calling `SendActivityAsync`, `UpdateActivityAsync`, or `DeleteActivityAsync` — no additional store lookup is needed at retry time), `Status` (Pending/Processing/Sent/Failed/DeadLettered), `RetryCount`, `NextRetryAt`, `CreatedAt`, `LastError`.
- [ ] Create EF Core migration for the `OutboxMessages` table with index on `Status` and `NextRetryAt`.
- [ ] Implement `OutboxRetryEngine` as `BackgroundService` that polls for pending messages, attempts delivery, and updates status.
- [ ] Implement exponential backoff retry: base delay 2s, multiplier 2×, computed delays of 2s, 4s, 8s, 16s with ±25% jitter, max delay cap 60s, up to 4 retries after initial attempt (5 total attempts) per the canonical retry policy in `tech-spec.md` §4.4. Dead-letter after final failed attempt.
- [ ] Implement `Retry-After` header handling: when the Bot Framework returns HTTP 429, parse the `Retry-After` response header and use its value as the minimum delay before the next retry attempt, overriding the computed backoff if `Retry-After` is longer.
- [ ] Implement token-bucket rate limiter in the outbound pipeline to proactively avoid Bot Framework rate limits (default: 50 msgs/sec per bot, configurable).
- [ ] Implement dead-letter handling: messages exceeding retry threshold are moved to `DeadLettered` status with the last error recorded.
- [ ] Wire `TeamsMessengerConnector.SendMessageAsync`, `TeamsMessengerConnector.SendQuestionAsync`, `TeamsProactiveNotifier.SendProactiveAsync`, `TeamsProactiveNotifier.SendProactiveQuestionAsync`, `TeamsProactiveNotifier.SendToChannelAsync`, and `TeamsProactiveNotifier.SendQuestionToChannelAsync` to persist outbound notifications to `IMessageOutbox.EnqueueAsync` BEFORE attempting delivery. The `OutboxRetryEngine` becomes the canonical send path: all outbound messages are first enqueued with `Status = Pending`, then picked up by the engine which calls `ContinueConversationAsync`. Direct sends in Stage 4.2 are replaced by outbox-mediated sends. This ensures no notification is lost even if the process crashes between intent-to-send and actual delivery, satisfying the reliability requirement to persist outbound notifications and retry transient failures.
- [ ] Wire Adaptive Card update and delete operations through the outbox for retry reliability: `UpdateActivityAsync` and `DeleteActivityAsync` calls in `TeamsCardLifecycleService` (Stage 3.3's concrete `ITeamsCardLifecycleService` implementation — the SOLE owner of card update/delete per Stage 2.1's interface contract) are refactored to persist to `IMessageOutbox.EnqueueAsync` with `DestinationType` set to `CardUpdate` or `CardDelete` respectively, so that transient failures on card update/delete are retried by `OutboxRetryEngine` using the same exponential backoff policy as send operations. `TeamsCardLifecycleService.UpdateCardToResolvedAsync` and `DeleteCardAsync` each call `ICardStateStore.GetByQuestionIdAsync(questionId)` to retrieve `ActivityId`, `ConversationId`, and `ConversationReferenceJson`, then enqueue an `OutboxMessages` entry with those fields. At retry time, `OutboxRetryEngine` deserializes `ConversationReferenceJson` to rehydrate the Bot Framework conversation context via `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync`, then calls `UpdateActivityAsync(activityId)` or `DeleteActivityAsync(activityId)` inside the proactive callback. This satisfies `e2e-scenarios.md` §Adaptive Card update retry on transient failure (lines 542-547) which requires retry on transient Adaptive Card update failure.
- [ ] Refactor `TeamsProactiveNotifier`, `TeamsMessengerConnector`, and `TeamsCardLifecycleService` to remove direct `ContinueConversationAsync`, `UpdateActivityAsync`, and `DeleteActivityAsync` calls from their send/update/delete methods: each method now only calls `IMessageOutbox.EnqueueAsync` to persist the operation, and `OutboxRetryEngine.ProcessPendingAsync` is the sole code path that invokes `ContinueConversationAsync`, `UpdateActivityAsync`, or `DeleteActivityAsync`. Verify by confirming no direct Bot Framework API calls remain in `TeamsProactiveNotifier`, `TeamsMessengerConnector`, or `TeamsCardLifecycleService` after this step.

### Dependencies
- _none — start stage_

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Successful delivery — Given a message is enqueued with status `Pending`, When `OutboxRetryEngine` runs and delivery succeeds, Then the status is updated to `Sent`.
- [ ] Scenario: Transient failure retry — Given delivery fails with a transient `HttpRequestException`, When `OutboxRetryEngine` runs, Then `RetryCount` is incremented and `NextRetryAt` is set with exponential backoff.
- [ ] Scenario: Dead-letter after max retries — Given a message has failed 5 times, When `OutboxRetryEngine` runs, Then the status is set to `DeadLettered` and `LastError` contains the failure reason.
- [ ] Scenario: Outbox is canonical send path — Given `TeamsProactiveNotifier.SendProactiveAsync` is called with a message for `user-1`, When the method executes, Then the message is first persisted to `OutboxMessages` with `Status = Pending` before any `ContinueConversationAsync` call, and the `OutboxRetryEngine` picks it up for actual delivery.
- [ ] Scenario: Card update retry on transient failure — Given an Adaptive Card update operation is enqueued with `DestinationType = CardUpdate` and the first `UpdateActivityAsync` call fails with a transient HTTP 502 error, When `OutboxRetryEngine` retries, Then the update succeeds on the second attempt, the card reflects the approved state, and no duplicate confirmation is sent to the user (per `e2e-scenarios.md` §Adaptive Card update retry on transient failure lines 542-547).
- [ ] Scenario: CardUpdate outbox rehydrates conversation context — Given a `CardUpdate` outbox entry with `ActivityId = "act-upd"`, `ConversationId = "conv-1"`, and `ConversationReferenceJson` containing a serialized `ConversationReference` with `ServiceUrl = "https://smba.trafficmanager.net/teams/"`, When `OutboxRetryEngine` processes this entry, Then it deserializes `ConversationReferenceJson` into a `ConversationReference`, calls `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync` with the deserialized reference to create a proactive turn, and calls `turnContext.UpdateActivityAsync("act-upd")` inside the callback — proving the retry engine can rehydrate the Bot Framework conversation context from stored data alone without an active user turn.
- [ ] Scenario: CardDelete outbox rehydrates conversation context — Given a `CardDelete` outbox entry with `ActivityId = "act-del"`, `ConversationReferenceJson` containing a valid serialized reference, When `OutboxRetryEngine` processes this entry, Then it deserializes the reference, calls `CloudAdapter.ContinueConversationAsync`, and calls `turnContext.DeleteActivityAsync("act-del")` inside the proactive callback.

## Stage 6.2: Duplicate Suppression and Idempotency

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Create `IdempotencyStore` with a `ProcessedActions` table containing: `QuestionId` + `UserId` composite key, `ActionValue`, `ProcessedAt`, `ExpiresAt`. This provides domain-level idempotency for Adaptive Card action callbacks (per `architecture.md` §2.16 distinction: transport-level deduplication on `Activity.Id` is handled by `ActivityDeduplicationMiddleware` registered in the bot adapter pipeline in Stage 2.1; this domain-level store catches semantically duplicate card actions that arrive as distinct activities).
- [ ] Implement domain-level idempotency check in `CardActionHandler`: before processing an Adaptive Card action, check if the `(QuestionId, UserId)` pair has already been processed in `IdempotencyStore`. If so, return the previous result without re-executing.
- [ ] Add cleanup background job to purge expired entries from `ProcessedActions` (default TTL: 24 hours).
- [ ] Implement outbound deduplication: `SendMessageAsync` checks if a message with the same `CorrelationId` + `DestinationId` was already sent within a configurable window.

### Dependencies
- phase-reliability-and-performance/stage-outbox-pattern-and-retry-engine

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Duplicate card action suppressed — Given user `user-1` already approved question `q-1` (recorded in `ProcessedActions` with composite key `(QuestionId="q-1", UserId="user-1")`), When the same user submits `approve` for `q-1` again via a distinct `Activity.Id`, Then the domain-level idempotency check in `CardActionHandler` returns the previous result without re-executing.
- [ ] Scenario: Non-duplicate card action processed — Given no entry exists in `ProcessedActions` for `(QuestionId="q-2", UserId="user-1")`, When the user submits `approve` for `q-2`, Then the action is processed normally and recorded in `ProcessedActions`.
- [ ] Scenario: Expired ProcessedActions entries cleaned — Given a `ProcessedActions` entry with `ExpiresAt` older than 24 hours, When the cleanup background job runs, Then the entry is removed from the `ProcessedActions` table.
- [ ] Scenario: Outbound deduplication — Given a message with `CorrelationId = "c-1"` and `DestinationId = "d-1"` was already sent within the deduplication window, When `SendMessageAsync` is called with the same `CorrelationId` + `DestinationId`, Then the duplicate send is suppressed.

## Stage 6.3: Performance Monitoring and Health Checks

### Implementation Steps
- [ ] Add OpenTelemetry instrumentation to `TeamsMessengerConnector`: trace spans for `SendMessageAsync`, `SendQuestionAsync`, and `ReceiveAsync` with attributes `correlationId`, `messageType`, `destinationType`.
- [ ] Add custom metrics: `teams.messages.sent` (counter), `teams.messages.received` (counter), `teams.card.delivery.duration_ms` (histogram), `teams.outbox.queue_depth` (gauge).
- [ ] Implement health check for Bot Framework connectivity: verify token endpoint reachability and adapter initialization.
- [ ] Implement health check for conversation reference store: verify database connectivity and reference count.
- [ ] Add structured logging with Serilog enrichers for `CorrelationId`, `TenantId`, `UserId` on every log entry.

### Dependencies
- phase-reliability-and-performance/stage-duplicate-suppression-and-idempotency

### Test Scenarios
- [ ] Scenario: Trace span emitted — Given a message is sent via `SendMessageAsync`, When the operation completes, Then an OpenTelemetry span named `TeamsConnector.SendMessage` is recorded with `correlationId` attribute.
- [ ] Scenario: Delivery histogram — Given 100 outbound messages are enqueued to `OutboxMessages`, When the `OutboxRetryEngine` picks them up and delivers via Bot Connector, Then `teams.card.delivery.duration_ms` has 100 observations measuring the interval from queue pickup (when `OutboxRetryEngine` dequeues) to Bot Connector HTTP acknowledgement, with P95 below 3000ms (per `tech-spec.md` §4.4 and `e2e-scenarios.md` §Performance).
- [ ] Scenario: Health check degraded — Given the database is unreachable, When `/health` is called, Then it returns `Degraded` with detail `ConversationReferenceStore: Unhealthy`.

